I disagree with the behavior that is being added here, at least in the context of using vlans. When creating an external network, I expect it to allocate a VLAN like any other tenant network. There shouldn't be anything 'special' about external networks at the ML2 layer. That flag should only indicate the behavior of how routers interact with it.

Otherwise we end up in this unsustainable scenario of having a flag mean excessive amounts of behavior changes that become impossible to keep consistent across all of Neutron."}, {'account_id': 10370, 'date': '2015-02-12 06:14:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: -Code-Review

After some discussion on #openstack-neutron, I see Kevin has a valid use case for having external networks being allocated just like tenant networks. 

I suggest adding a new default_external_network_type config variable. If its value is "" (empty), then external networks are allocated just like normal tenant networks (based on the tenant_network_types config). If its not "", then it specifies the type to allocate when external=True and no provider attributes are specified. It could default to 'local' I think. At init, we'd validate that its value, if set, is supported by the loaded type drivers.'}, {'account_id': 10370, 'date': '2015-02-13 12:18:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

I'm still not sure about additional option.
In most cases creating external network is a one time task performed by admin (who presumably knows what he's doing).

I'd prefer to solve it differently: for example, if provider networks extension is enabled, require specifying network type for external network, e.g. fail network creation request with appropriate exception if network type is not specified.

May be it makes sense to bring this to broader audience and look for another opinion?"}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2015-03-26 16:33:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 27: Code-Review+1

I'm happy with this as-is, and would also have been happy with defaulting to 'local' for external networks when no providernet or multiprovidernet attributes are supplied. But given that some ML2 back-ends implement external connectivity at the edge and thus need normal tenant network allocation for external networks instead of local, I feel the approach here is a good compromise."}, {'account_id': 6524, 'date': '2015-03-26 17:19:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 27: Code-Review+2

This config option is a nice compromise to the different approaches to dealing with external networks."}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2015-03-27 08:17:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 27:

[{'created': '2015-01-23 09:37:33.000000000', 'message': "External Networks in ML2 have invalid providernet types

With the ML2 Plugin, every network created has segments with
provider:network_types being tenant_network_types.
When applied to external networks, the types that could be in
tenant_network_types parameter (like vxlan or gre) are not appropriate.

This patch makes external networks have segments with the 'local'
provider:network_type when the network_type is not explicitly set
instead of values in tenant_network_types.

Closes-Bug: #1328991

Change-Id: Idbbe6bced73cfedbe0f8e7abba35f87589b1a004
Co-Authored-By: Romil Gupta <romilg@hp.com>

commit_message:
Added config variable for External Network type in ML2

Description:
With the ML2 Plugin, every network created has segments with
provider:network_types being tenant_network_types.
When applied to external networks, the types that could be in
tenant_network_types parameter (like vxlan or gre) are not appropriate.

Implementation:
Added new config variable 'external_network_type' in ml2_conf.ini
which contains the default network type for external networks
when no provider attributes are specified, by default it is None.

It also includes small code re-factoring/renaming of import statement.

DocImpact

Closes-Bug: #1328991

Co-Authored-By: Romil Gupta <romilg@hp.com>

Change-Id: Idbbe6bced73cfedbe0f8e7abba35f87589b1a004

commit_message:
Define API_VERSIONS in shell.py

Since Idec8e88fe9621f10ec4b7eecd90708fb3730f56f python-openstackclient expects
API_VERSION to be defined in the plugin. While this has always been a
documented requirement[1], this is the first time it's been enforced in the
code apparently.

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/python-openstackclient/plugins.html

Change-Id: I79bad8e5d09021dc266d6d3b3a4c7b73bcb7d187
(cherry picked from commit 21f0ac93b9a797d6bfca9823188bfe7363472704)

Switch to new style policy language

New style policy language is much more human readable and the prefered
way to describe policies.

Change-Id: Ib741e2222ad36fa481ca8003387ecc1d9e8231e6
Implements: blueprint switch-to-new-style-policy-lang

commit_message:
Add xags=STORAGE to physical wwpn query

Because of recent pypowervm changes to default group = None the
vios.py method get_physical_wwpns must be updated to provide
xags=STORAGE.

Change-Id: I37bdc14b57536eeedb606b5b4fe6c1051ee5a888

In v2, endpoint create takes all 3 urls - admin, public, and internal, and creates all of them at once.  This is reflected in the 3 url parameters to keystone_endpoint.rb and endpoint.pp.
With v3, the semantics of openstack endpoint create changes quite a bit - you have to create each url separately.
I don't think we need to change endpoint.pp and keystone_endpoint.rb.  Can we just change the provider to create/ensure all 3 endpoints with separate calls to 'openstack endpoint ...'?  Or is that not 'the puppet way'?"}, {'account_id': 6525, 'date': '2015-04-15 07:29:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1 Workflow-1

Another divide and conquer (I hope!),
This review could be abandoned and placed by the following https://review.openstack.org/173708
plus another one for endpoints only to follow.'}, {'account_id': 6525, 'date': '2015-04-17 11:30:17.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Replaced with https://review.openstack.org/173708'}]

commit_message:
service and endpoint v3

Keystone API V3 must become the default since V2 is deprecated

But having V3 doesn't preclude setting up v2.0 endpoints for clients
needing backward compatibility

To break it down the changes, this patch will come along other complementing reviews
mainly for the other keystone providers.

RSPEC not finished yet

Change-Id: Ib51ceeedcf4bb9123d22fe299f87451a4d2fb101

commit_message:
Correct mock use in TestCommandLineArgument.setUp

TestCommandLineArgument.setUp mocks get_keystone_client using:

  shell.client.Client.get_keystone_client = mock.MagicMock()

which is incorrect ... as the mock is not clean up during
tearDown/cleanup.

This change corrects how the mock is done.

Closes-Bug: #1445197
Change-Id: If03a27f78fccd8bc5000b258f429dfb6f770f5ee

RN6.0-updates: Minor fix in command

Change the incorrect command
 python mos_apply_mu.py --env-id=X --update --all-envs
 to
 python mos_apply_mu.py --update --all-envs

commit_message:
Add HP monitoring playbook

This commit adds a playbook to create the appropriate checks/alarms for
use with the hp_monitoring.py plugin in the rpc-maas repo.

This will add checks/alarms that provide equivalent functionality to
that currently available for Dell hardware.

Change-Id: I1fd4441606931113ac2fb0abe9ba14311da944f2
Closes-Bug: #1441189

commit_message:
Add screenshot about Fuel CLI warning and edit notes

Currently, User, Operations and Reference Architectures
Guides have poor notes about the changes made
via Fuel CLI and web browser (what takes precedence
and what message appears to warn a user).

This commit adds the required screenshots and
provides some minor changes for the note code.

Change-Id: I739c6db78cf688d5342110d752f8e2631b2be2b6
Closes-Bug: 1374944
(cherry picked from commit 9ee0481fc268b538aa3ecd7841776631b8fbf10a)

commit_message:
Use openstack CLI instead of keystone

When running './redstack install' multiple messages are output stating
that the keystone CLI has been deprecated. These calls should be
replaced to ones utilizing the openstack CLI program instead.

Note: There is still one message output, due to uploading to glance.
This needs to be fixed in devstack.

Change-Id: Icdc5370a944898a04e3665102a4195415523ca44
Closes-Bug: #1441340

commit_message:
Add screenshot about Fuel CLI warning and edit notes

Currently, User, Operations and Reference Architectures
Guides have poor notes about the changes made
via Fuel CLI and web browser (what takes precedence
and what message appears to warn a user).

This commit adds the required screenshots and
provides some minor changes for the note code.

Change-Id: I739c6db78cf688d5342110d752f8e2631b2be2b6
Closes-Bug: 1374944

commit_message:
Load docker images on install if Docker is running

fuel-docker-images will extract and load Fuel Docker
images if the package is installed while docker
daemon is running running.

Default behavior on Fuel Master install will load this
package during Anaconda, while docker daemon is not
running.

blueprint package-fuel-components

Change-Id: I254933582da19d7905c595c7eab6d5d74f2ad06f

commit_message:
Fix https stack trace on python 3.4 client

When using the client with python 3.4 and no ssl compression the following
stack trace ocurrs:

 TypeError: startswith first arg must be bytes or a tuple of bytes, not str

Closes-bug: 1442883
Related-bug: 1357430
Change-Id: I8e28f0bb1f3e866f11851247ce31470ca8c2af4f
(cherry picked from commit bd0aa0672e0ebb5dfaa2178a8ffce79be143524b)

swift_hosts[0] between juno and kilo, we need to copy these build files
up to swift_hosts[0] in order for an upgrade to work.

The tasks added will work on complete kilo installs (as the copy simply
won't do anything) - so its safe to leave in, but can be removed for

commit_message:
Fix ring distribute from juno to kilo

Since the location the ring was built changed from localhost to
swift_hosts[0] between juno and kilo, we need to copy these build files
up to swift_hosts[0] in order for an upgrade to work.

The tasks added will work on complete kilo installs (as the copy simply
won't do anything) - so its safe to leave in, but can be removed for
Liberty.

Change-Id: I285ef99aa5746754f5da4b1638dd7d76fe626602
Closes-Bug: #1443883

commit_message:
remove cinder data from test_vcenter.py

There was checkbox "Cinder" on VMware tab wich was removed on
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/169830/ But our tests steel send this
data when creates cluster.

This patch-set just does corresponding changes in system tests.

commit_message:
[install-guide] [yum] install openstack-glance-{api,registry}

On RedHat-based distributions it is now necessary to install
openstack-glance-api and openstack-glance-registry instead of
openstack-glance.

Partially implements bp installguide-kilo.

Change-Id: I2695b30e02d168c9325e8c1d3533deea247b1915

commit_message:
Apply input schema to workflow/action input

* apply the schema introduced in previous
  patch(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/172438/).
* add some unit tests accordingly.

things need to be done in the subsequent patches:
- consider the input default value when validating inputs of
  workflow/action.
- add some unit tests for input default value.
- add some samples in mistral-extra repository if needed.

Partially Implements: blueprint mistral-default-input-values

Change-Id: I9737dbffe0e6913d976990fbdc31086539b5956e

commit_message:
Show ports from shared nets in floating IP assoc

Ports from shared networks should be included in the list
of 'Ports to be associated' even though a router interface
connecting to the external network might not be visible to
the tenant.

Conflicts:
	openstack_dashboard/api/neutron.py
	openstack_dashboard/test/api_tests/network_tests.py

Change-Id: Iba141b51371b955c3cfdcc52c0bf279466131713
Closes-Bug: #1394051
(cherry picked from commit be9f5738d563a8b2444cbdf283c0884bd2f37ab4)

[{'created': '2015-04-17 04:33:35.000000000', 'message': 'Catch exception when evaluate single alarm

Currently, if we raise exception when evaluate alarms, the outside
method will not catch it, so the higher _evaluate_assigned_alarms
catches it, but this will stop evaluating the rest alarms. Alarm

commit_message:
Catch exception when evaluate single alarm

Currently, if we raise exception when evaluate alarms, the outside
method will not catch it, so the higher _evaluate_assigned_alarms
catches it, but this will stop evaluating the rest alarms. Alarm
should be evaluated no matter whether other alarms succeed or not.

This patch adds a try...except block in _evaluate_alarm, it will
log exception when it is raised, and the higher method can move
on next alarm.

Change-Id: Id95865c51dc4ffe2d7089a3ff4fa5b73bd93ae76
Closes-Bug: #1408620
(cherry picked from commit f88f6863eaf70de74e63a11fbce1c23033141aea)

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-04 04:32:51.000000000', 'message': 'Abstract rm/chmod shell commands in guestagent

The guestagent commonly executes basic shell commands
across multiple files and datastores.
Each datastore currently scripts its own shell calls.
Apart from cluttering the Python code with shell constructs,
it also makes maintenance of the shell calls more difficult by
requiring the same change be made across multiple lines,
source files and/or potentially even datastores.

The goal of this patch set is to provide a simple straightforward
interface for most common shell calls used across the guestagent
code while encapsulating the related shell code into a single module.

This patch set includes refactoring of 'rm' and 'chmod' calls.
It also introduces unit tests ('guestagent/test_operating_system')
for the above implementations.

The shell code was moved into 'common/operating_system' module.
The replacing interface is:

def remove(path, force=False, recursive=True, **kwargs):
    """Remove a given file or directory (by default as root).

def chmod(path, modes, recursive=True, force=False, **kwargs):
    """Changes the mode of a given file (by default as root).
    The call is a no-op if no modes are provided.

The calls also take optional keyword arguments:
    :param run_as_root:      Execute as root (default).
    :type run_as_root:       boolean

    :param timeout:          Number of seconds if specified,
                             default if not.
                             There is no timeout if set to None.
    :type timeout:           integer

Notes on the representation of file permissions (modes):

Generally, one can 'reset' (set modes to an exact value) or
'add'/'remove' modes to/from the current mode.
The above operations are represented by a new 'operating_system.Modes'
class.
For example, the read permission for all can be represented in the octal
form as '444'.
Mode on a given file can be 'reset' to this exact value
(chmod =444 "path")
The permissions can be added to (chmod +444 "path")
... or removed from the current mode (chmod -444 "path")

The Modes constructor takes three optional lists of octal modes (flags),
one for each of the above operations.

"chmod u+x,g=rw,o=r" can be then represented as:
Modes(reset=[0064], add=[0100])
or
Modes(reset=[0040, 0020, 0004], add=[0100])
or
Modes(reset=[0040 | 0020 | 0004], add=[0100])

See the Python 'stat' module for available flags also accepted by the
Python build-in functions such as 'os.chmod'.

Change-Id: Idbfa05fdc5c48aed31989578f828a7f57aca3be2
Closes-Bug: 1438429
Related-Bug: 1431618
Related-Bug: 1438430

def remove(path, force=False, recursive=True, **kwargs):
    """Remove a given file or directory (by default as root).

def chmod(path, reset=None, add=None, remove=None, recursive=True,
          force=False, **kwargs):
    """Changes the mode of a given file (by default as root).
    The way the modes get applied is generally controlled by the operation
    ('reset', 'add', 'remove') group to which they belong.
    All modes are represented as octal numbers and are combined in a
    'bitwise OR' (|) operation.
    The modes are always applied in this order: reset (=), add (+), remove (-)

The calls also take optional keyword arguments:
    :param run_as_root:      Execute as root (default).
    :type run_as_root:       boolean

    :param timeout:          Number of seconds if specified,
                             default if not.
                             There is no timeout if set to None.
    :type timeout:           integer

"chmod u+x,g=rw,o=r" can be represented as:
chmod(reset=[0064], add=[0100])
or
chmod(reset=[0040, 0020, 0004], add=[0100])
or
chmod(reset=[0040 | 0020 | 0004], add=[0100])

See 'operating_system.FileMode' struct for some common file modes.
See the Python 'stat' module for more flags also accepted by the
Python build-in functions such as 'os.chmod'.

Change-Id: Idbfa05fdc5c48aed31989578f828a7f57aca3be2
Closes-Bug: 1438429
Related-Bug: 1431618
Related-Bug: 1438430

    :param run_as_root:      Execute as root (default).

or

See 'operating_system.FileMode' struct for some common file modes.
See the Python 'stat' module for more flags also accepted by the
Python build-in functions such as 'os.chmod'.

commit_message:
Abstract rm/chmod shell commands in guestagent

The guestagent commonly executes basic shell commands
across multiple files and datastores.
Each datastore currently scripts its own shell calls.
Apart from cluttering the Python code with shell constructs,
it also makes maintenance of the shell calls more difficult by
requiring the same change be made across multiple lines,
source files and/or potentially even datastores.

The goal of this patch set is to provide a simple straightforward
interface for most common shell calls used across the guestagent
code while encapsulating the related shell code into a single module.

This patch set includes refactoring of 'rm' and 'chmod' calls.
It also introduces unit tests ('guestagent/test_operating_system')
for the above implementations.

The shell code was moved into 'common/operating_system' module.
The replacing interface is:

def remove(path, force=False, recursive=True, **kwargs):
    """Remove a given file or directory.

def chmod(path, mode, recursive=True, force=False, **kwargs):
    """Changes the mode of a given file.

The calls also take optional keyword arguments:
    :param as_root:          Execute as root.
    :type as_root:           boolean

    :param timeout:          Number of seconds if specified,
                             default if not.
                             There is no timeout if set to None.
    :type timeout:           integer

Notes on the representation of file permissions (modes):

Generally, one can 'reset' (set modes to an exact value) or
'add'/'remove' modes to/from the current mode.
The above operations are represented by a new
'operating_system.FileMode' class.
For example, the read permission for all can be represented in the octal
form as '444'.
Mode on a given file can be 'reset' to this exact value
(chmod =444 "path")
The permissions can be added to (chmod +444 "path")
... or removed from the current mode (chmod -444 "path")

The Modes constructor takes three optional lists of octal modes (flags),
one for each of the above operations.

"chmod u+x,g=rw,o=r" can be represented as:
FileMode(reset=[0064], add=[0100])
or
FileMode(reset=[0040, 0020, 0004], add=[0100])
or
FileMode(reset=[0040 | 0020 | 0004], add=[0100])

See 'operating_system.FileMode' struct for some common file modes.
See the Python 'stat' module for more flags also accepted by the
Python build-in functions such as 'os.chmod'.

Change-Id: Idbfa05fdc5c48aed31989578f828a7f57aca3be2
Closes-Bug: 1438429
Related-Bug: 1431618
Related-Bug: 1438430

commit_message:
Stop encrypted disk on instance suspend/power off

Disconnecting dm-crypt device from an encrypted LVM volume while the
instance is suspended or powered off will secure user data from
unauthorized access. This will extend data at-rest protection provided
by the LVM ephemeral storage encryption feature.

SecurityImpact

Change-Id: Ie948ccc999f79300d7449944406f063d62a95533
Implements: blueprint stop-dmcrypt-on-suspend
Previouly-approved: kilo (I6070754d998abc73c8a2e03025700da71dcdafbe)

commit_message:
Create /etc/resolv.conf as a link

resolvconf service manages /run/resolvconf/resolv.conf by default on
Ubuntu 12.04 and 14.04. resolv.conf should be symlink to it.

Closes-Bug: 1434232
Change-Id: I501538326c095e47adafae476c2c3a299509fa84
Signed-off-by: Sergii Golovatiuk <sgolovatiuk@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Openvswitch packages should be installed only if use_ovs=>true

This patch change following:
* don't install ovs packages if it is not required
* don't check ovs service if use_ovs == false
* no more usage of ovs-vsctl in commands for lnx provider
  if ovs-vsctl is in commands - puppet invalidates provider
  due to external tools can't be executed

Closes-bug: #1442672
Change-Id: I7ca7bfaa5fddc704c824df81b6e5a5a32ca726ca

I thing we have three sides of problem with huge amount of logs included to the snapshot:
1) It takes long time to get them, and it is quite often that snapshot task ends by timeout (default 60 mins), and confusing user.
2) When snaphot is creating it making a copy of whole /var/log/ to /var/www/nailgun/dump
On big environments there is not enough space, and task failed
3) Resulting snapshot is huge, and it is pain to transfer it.

Having remove_sub_dirs function is great, it may allow us include whole /var/log/, but exclude /var/log/remote, and make selection of remote logs more accurate, e.g. for per-environment snapshots,

However, remove_sub_dirs function
solves only number 3)
Can we modify it to solve parts 1 and 2 too, by not fetching the dir at all?

Same in this Dimtriy's commit https://review.openstack.org/#/c/155349/ 
in function remove_matched_files"}, {'account_id': 11082, 'date': '2015-04-12 07:42:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Add possibilities to skip subdirs in snapshots

* added tests
* modified snapshot settings to exclude files from atop
  and copy only atop_current file
* add posibilities to skip dirs and files using unix syntax
  now files can be skiped by construction eg **/*.gz when
  we want to skip all gz. files in all subdirs

Change-Id: I73fdc932d53d75bafd7386555f95e88536d29a25
Closes-Bug: #1429112
DocImpact

commit_message:
Mask passwords with iscsiadm commands

This patch adds the fix that exists in the nova
libvirt volume code to use oslo_utils strutils
to mask passwords that might show up in debug log
messages.

Change-Id: I5c321d6b2627f186ff3dfe64ee7ad71f27a95cf0
Closes-Bug: 1445137

commit_message:
Add support for provider network in tempest

This commit adds support for using provider network
in tempest if it's desired by the user of devstack.
It changed network_for_ssh and fixed_network_name in
[compute] to the PHYSICAL_NETWORK specified by the user.

Change-Id: Ib0047998eb6ab469a64401274a7658a089c75a74

commit_message:
puppet: add missing ::glance include on controller

On Controller node, we also need to include ::glance if we want to have
common Glance bits (packaging included).
This is a Puppet best practice.

Change-Id: I967c06b2c78d8f3aa5fa984b518d34c813426a2e

commit_message:
Define API_VERSIONS in shell.py

Since Idec8e88fe9621f10ec4b7eecd90708fb3730f56f python-openstackclient expects
API_VERSION to be defined in the plugin. While this has always been a
documented requirement[1], this is the first time it's been enforced in the
code apparently.

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/python-openstackclient/plugins.html

Change-Id: I79bad8e5d09021dc266d6d3b3a4c7b73bcb7d187

commit_message:
Add locking to PureISCSIDriver around creating Purity Host objects.

This will prevent us from getting conflicting credentials for
connection methods which will result in iSCSI attach operations to fail.

Change-Id: Ia206e7b5ff330c8fccb49ed23a31b120a5c04eb3
Closes-Bug: 1444224

commit_message:
Config Reference: Add readded cinder drivers

Cinder removed a couple of Block Storage drivers and has re-added some
of them again. Add these again to the Config Reference:
* Windows driver (change I0b078a60e8d9c95d12185d1ff3ffe74fb71f10ab)
* Huawei (change Iad7c1afff1a932876255a37fc0b5bf5993246aaa)
* ZFSSA NFS (change Ibf830f295043624ca9a5dc90f1e3a897cb64915f)
* NetApp (change Idd7e3bd0df393f61ba9c5011166b7d5ba196753b)

Change-Id: I9a7df71deec48ef6b75fabbd4d65ded2d094f61a

commit_message:
Add "About" dialog

In Horizon, "About" dialog is added under user settings
drop-down menu.

Conflicts:
        openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/info/templates/info/index.html

Change-Id: I8e2da707b64d475e76fb8739fe1d7c0813505872
Closes-bug: #1382169

commit_message:
Add MariaDB/Galera section

The current MySQL with Galera section is targetting Debian-based
distros. Red Hat-based distros include MariaDB with Galera, so a
section specifying how to configure it is added.

Change-Id: Ib5dcf1a36a38ab87860182d6ec5d21c9995451dd

I don't think this going to do what you want it to do.

1. It just silently drops the markers from ``install_requires`` and ``tests_require``, it doesn't actually attempt to interpret them. It should either dynamically filter things out based on executing the markers, or it should use the setuptools markers support to handle it (which will automatically be translated into Wheels as well).
2. It only parses the install_requires and tests_requires from a setup.cfg, while I think that openstack *should* use install_requires inside of a setup.cfg, I don't think that's what they are actually doing now. IOW this doesn't have any effect on your requirements.txt files."}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2015-03-24 15:04:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

what is " the setuptools markers support to handle it ", from what I understood it does not support them?'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-04-15 20:48:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Julien: could you please elaborate the use case?

I tried to use environment markers in requirements-py3.txt of Oslo Messaging:

futures>=2.1.6; python_version < '3.2'

"tox -e py34" failed because pip of .tox/py34/ is pip 1.5.6. But when I upgraded pip to the latest version (6.1.1), "pip install -r requirements-py3.txt -r test-requirements-py3.txt" just works.

Why not putting somewhere a requirement on pip >= 6.0 (first version supporting environment markers in requirements) instead of trying to ignore them?

At least, you should only strip environment markers if you have pip older than 6.0.

But it's unclear to me when the check on the pip version must be done. pbr can be used to build a source distribution, but the source can be installed by another version of pip which supports environment markers...'}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2015-04-15 22:02:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Victor: here's the case https://review.openstack.org/#/c/164994/

Tell me how I make it work. ;-)"}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-04-16 07:49:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> Victor: here's the case https://review.openstack.org/#/c/164994/ Tell me how I make it work. ;-)

Oh, I'm no more able to create a fresh tox virtual env using environment markers in requirements.txt, strange :-) Yesterday it worked.

tox calls "pip install -U -e .../oslo-incubator" which calls "python setup.py egg_info" and this command fails on list(pkg_resources.parse_requirements(value)) in check_requirements().

I confirm that list(pkg_resources.parse_requirements(["trollius>=1.0; python_version > '3'"])) fails on Python 2.7 and 3.4. The pkg_resources comes from the standard library, but check_requirements() is part of setuptools.

I modified locally check_requirements() in setuptools/dist.py to strip environment markers from requirements. With this modification, "python setup.py egg_info" works. I also built a source distribution (.tar.gz), I was able to install with "python setup.py install" outside tox venv. In tox venv, "python setup.py bdist_wheel" fails'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-04-16 07:51:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(Oops, I sent my comment too early.)

(..)  In tox venv, "python setup.py bdist_wheel" fails in convert_requirements() of wheel/metadata.py:

Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "setup.py", line 30, in <module>
    pbr=True)
  File "/usr/lib64/python2.7/distutils/core.py", line 151, in setup
    dist.run_commands()
  File "/usr/lib64/python2.7/distutils/dist.py", line 953, in run_commands
    self.run_command(cmd)
  File "/usr/lib64/python2.7/distutils/dist.py", line 972, in run_command
    cmd_obj.run()
  File ".../python2.7/site-packages/wheel/bdist_wheel.py", line 228, in run
    self.distinfo_dir)
  File ".../python2.7/site-packages/wheel/bdist_wheel.py", line 370, in egg2dist
    pkg_info = self._pkginfo_to_metadata(egginfo_path, pkginfo_path)
  File ".../python2.7/site-packages/wheel/bdist_wheel.py", line 280, in _pkginfo_to_metadata
    return metadata.pkginfo_to_metadata(egg_info_path, pkginfo_path)
  File ".../python2.7/site-packages/wheel/metadata.py", line 247, in pkginfo_to_metadata
    for new_req in convert_requirements(reqs):
  File ".../python2.7/site-packages/wheel/metadata.py", line 219, in convert_requirements
    parsed_requirement = pkg_resources.Requirement.parse(req)
  File ".../python2.7/site-packages/pkg_resources/__init__.py", line 2966, in parse
    reqs = list(parse_requirements(s))
  File ".../python2.7/site-packages/pkg_resources/__init__.py", line 2910, in parse_requirements
    "version spec")
  File ".../python2.7/site-packages/pkg_resources/__init__.py", line 2875, in scan_list
    raise ValueError(msg, line, "at", line[p:])
ValueError: ('Expected version spec in', "argparse; python_version < '2.7'", 'at', "; python_version < '2.7'")'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-04-16 07:58:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> In tox venv, "python setup.py bdist_wheel" fails in convert_requirements() of wheel/metadata.py

I modified convert_requirements() to drop environment markers here too. Problem: METADATA and metadata.json files inside the generated wheel don't contain environment markers.

It looks like Python tools (pkg_resources, setuptools, pip, pbr) are not fully compatible with environment markers. I'm not sure which tool should be fixed to understand them. There are different constrains. IMO an important one is to be able to install a source or wheel distributions on older Python versions, what do you think?

This review is not the best place to discuss environment markers. Distutils-SIG mailing list is a better place:
https://mail.python.org/mailman/listinfo/distutils-sig'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-04-16 11:33:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

FYI I opened an issue in the wheel project to ask to support environment markers:
https://bitbucket.org/pypa/wheel/issue/139/wheel-should-support-pep-426-environment'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-04-16 23:46:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

So, what we need pbr to do is:
 - accept environment markers in all its inputs (setup.cfg, requirements.txt files etc)
 - preserve those and pass them onto other code appropriately - e.g. setuptools etc.
 - error when interacting with a too-old version of such a tool.
 - possibly, we might want to warn for a few releases rather than erroring.
 - *degrade gracefully* - that is, if a user doesn't use environment markers, we shouldn't require new enough versions of other tools. So if you opt in, you need the right tools. Otherwise you can ignore it.

We'll need to work with wheel and setuptools to get environment markers support in releases, where's not already.

Note that pkg_resources is already fixed - but you need a new enough version.

So, *this* patch as it stands is wrong."}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2015-04-17 07:22:55.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-04-17 07:24:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> FYI I opened an issue in the wheel project to ask to support environment markers: https://bitbucket.org/pypa/wheel/issue/139/wheel-should-support-pep-426-environment

>  - preserve those and pass them onto other code appropriately - e.g. setuptools etc.

Daniel Holth replied to my issue:

"""
Wheel's own setup.py provides an example. It is necessary to use the default extra "", which has the same effect as a setup_requires entry, to express requirements markers in setuptools. The extra name and the environment marker are separated by a colon :

extras_require={ ':python_version=="2.6"': ['argparse'], 'signatures': ['keyring'], ... },

It's better practice to just say == "2.6" since the comparisons are all string based.
"""

I don't know extra_require. Is it supported by setuptools and pip?'}]

commit_message:
Exclude LACP bonds checking from network verification

Currently network checker doesn't support
checking interfaces in bonds and checks it as
simple interfaces. But in case of LACP L2 bonding
verification fails on hardware. For 6.1 checking
interfaces in LACP bonds should be excluded

DocImpact
Closes-Bug:#1376908
Change-Id: Ie43ff2cdf350ab019d474799905a2cc1bb970480

commit_message:
Add support for customized cluster name

Current RBD driver assumes ceph cluster name to be 'ceph', for
cluster has a different name, the driver won't be able to connect
to the cluster.  This change add a new config option
'rbd_cluster_name' to address this issue.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I02ae1a255fd613fce291cc7ddf90cfd9175255a8
Closes-bug: #1444855

commit_message:
Have reset state handlers go through a shared list

To make it hopefully easier to understand the commonality
of this function and its handlers have the handlers be
defined at the top of the function and use the common list
in the node iteration routine when resetting/matching.

Change-Id: I288eb548172b2f6f35e2bd90683f2065d3aa02dc

commit_message:
Fix for OVSDB and Neutron (MYSQL) Tables
are not in Sync

The patch set fixes the problem described in the launchpad
bug 1444833 where the agent sends physical_switch_id is sent as None
to plugin as a part of update_ovsdb_changes rpc

Change-Id: I1a5f087eac4df8d39326ae344afe2fd4b159fc70
Closes-Bug: 1444833

commit_message:
Replace '--type' with '--name' for command 'openstack service create'

The parameter '--type' is deprecated and should be replaced with the
parameter '--name'.

WARNING: openstackclient.identity.v2_0.service.CreateService The
argument --type is deprecated, use service create --name <service-name>
type instead.

Partially implements bp installguide-kilo.

Change-Id: I9e53f85d069965e3a70d38b428516a139ba8b726

I would shorten the "NET" prefix into "N", and also shorten the postfix into "-n", otherwise we're cutting the sg_id too much. As in many other places in neutron we're playing a bit probability with uuid shortening/collision.

commit_message:
Set IPset hash type to 'net' instead of 'ip'

The previous hash type was 'ip' and this caused a major
issue with the allowed address pairs extension since it
results in CIDRs being passed to ipset. When the hash type
is 'ip', a CIDR is completely enumerated into all of its
addresses so 10.100.0.0/16 results in ~65k entries. This
meant a single allowed_address_pairs entry could easily
exhaust an entire set.

This patch changes the hash type to 'net', which is designed
to handle a CIDRs as a single entry.

This patch also changes the names of the ipsets because
creating an ipset with different parameters will cause an
error and our ipset manager code isn't robust enough to handle
that at this time. There is another ongoing patch to fix
that but it won't be ready in time.[1]

The related bug was closed by increasing the set limit, which
did alleviate the problem. However, this change would also
address the issue because the gate tests run an allowed address
pairs extension test with the CIDR mentioned above.

1. I59e2e1c090cb95ee1bd14dbb53b6ff2c5e2713fd

Related-Bug: #1439817
Closes-Bug: #1444397
Change-Id: I8177699b157cd3eac46e2f481f47b5d966c49b07

commit_message:
Support update a replication controller

Add the support to update a rc. Using the following command:
magnum rc-update <rc> <op> [<path=value>]

It depends on this patch: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/174209/

Change-Id: Ie268ea8445e9b10e4466fefea2a8ea9c44cb91f3
Partial-Bug: #1444383

Support update a service

magnum service-update <service> <op> [<path=value>]

It depends on this patch: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/174208/

[{'created': '2015-04-14 23:16:26.000000000', 'message': 'Pin oslo pip requirements

Closes-Bug: 1444192

Oslo.config 1.10.0 was released today https://pypi.python.org/pypi/oslo.config/1.10.0
python-keystone client pins to specific versions of oslo packages. (1.10.0 not allowed)
https://github.com/openstack/python-keystoneclient/commit/981c499c6c8cfba19bc19b6e1df55a3110b64089

So mistral needs to pin oslo.config to < 1.10.0. Same story for oslo.utils.

Change-Id: Iac7e97c5c9a98932c44cc165200c1e73729597f6
'}]
commit_message:
Pin oslo pip requirements

Closes-Bug: 1444192

Oslo.config 1.10.0 was released today https://pypi.python.org/pypi/oslo.config/1.10.0
python-keystone client pins to specific versions of oslo packages. (1.10.0 not allowed)
https://github.com/openstack/python-keystoneclient/commit/981c499c6c8cfba19bc19b6e1df55a3110b64089

So mistral needs to pin oslo.config to < 1.10.0. Same story for oslo.utils.

Change-Id: Iac7e97c5c9a98932c44cc165200c1e73729597f6

commit_message:
AlarmStateTransitionedEvent timestamp now in ms

This will ensure a unique timestamp. Influx V9 will only keep one
entry with the same timestamp

Some of the tests weren't using a numerica timestamp which caused
problems when the code tried to divide the timestamp by 1000

Change-Id: Ie0fefc61abe9a95503fa7611971a21ed2cb56224

commit_message:
Adds Mariadb-client to the Heat template

Previously, one would have to use nsenter or docker exec to
interact with the mariadb container. This patch adds mariadb
client support to the Fedora 21 instance, making it easier to
work with and test the mariadb-server container.

Change-Id: Iebfbd88b7ca6a86268e03e3e4cf4763dd46fd6a7

commit_message:
Disables firewalld for Heat-deployed Fedora instances

Previously, Heat was deploying Fedora21 instances with firewalld
enabled and running. It is well documented that firewalld causes
problems with OpenStack Neutron. That is becasue Neutron uses
iptables instead of firewalld for security filtering.

Change-Id: I25cb32984841423a7b1c44b55cd19b5b4588c9e8

commit_message:
First step in PDF building

Add pdf_document variable.
After adding rst2pdf.pdfbuilder to extensions, you can build PDF with:
sphinx-build -b pdf -t user_only source/ build

This is not nice yet but a starting point for others - thus I propose to
merge this.

commit_message:
V3 support for Service provider only

- Adds support for V3 api
- The resource name must be the service type at creating, as expected by
  openstack (OSC)
- Once created, the name of the resource is the service id in order to
  have uniqueness

Change-Id: Ib38a55e787da33628cd2492cb597e5cff0eee181
Depends-On: I53f6bdec003ca0ee770a9b91fc2a83eb30480efe

commit_message:
Fix validate-all-yaml.sh to check for files with yml extension

YAML files can have .yaml or .yml extension. Make `validate-all-yaml.sh`
check for *.yml files in addition to *.yaml files since we now have some
of these in our source tree.

This should help to prevent bogus YAML files to land in the repository.

Change-Id: Id59273680fc2424f7b636033b1d641efcaaeba22

commit_message:
Update decomp progress chart

This patch updates the progress chart, now that the first cycle after the
decomp started. For the fully decomposed plugins/drivers and for known
projects that integrate with  Neutron, this patch proposes a new
summary table that provides a go-to reference for everything Neutron related.

Related-blueprint: core-vendor-decomposition

Change-Id: Ib79a7b6d1401f1d9241621ae03cf6692685e12b1

subject: [install-guide] create _member_ role
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 167, 'name': 'Christian Berendt', 'email': 'berendt@osism.tech', 'username': 'berendt'}, {'_account_id': 6547, 'name': 'Andreas Jaeger', 'email': 'jaegerandi@gmail.com', 'username': 'jaegerandi'}, {'_account_id': 6843, 'name': 'Phil Hopkins', 'email': 'phil.hopkins@rackspace.com', 'username': 'phil-hopkins-a'}, {'_account_id': 7007, 'name': 'Pranav Salunke', 'email': 'dguitarbite@gmail.com', 'username': 'dguitarbite'}, {'_account_id': 9162, 'name': 'Lana Brindley', 'email': 'openstack@lanabrindley.com', 'username': 'loquacity'}, {'_account_id': 9515, 'name': 'Matthew Kassawara', 'email': 'mkassawara@gmail.com', 'username': 'ionosphere80'}]
messages:
[{'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2015-04-15 15:43:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-04-15 15:51:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Did you see if keystone automatically created the _member_ role when you created the demo user? Juno worked this way, and we removed manual creation of the _member_ role because it created conflicts on some distributions depending on their default configuration. In Kilo, this logic stays the same. On Ubuntu with Kilo, keystone creates the _member_ role automatically. However, in Kilo, creating the _member_ role manually when it already exists shouldn't throw an error like it did in Juno."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-15 19:41:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-openstack-manuals-tox-checklinks http://logs.openstack.org/51/173951/1/check/gate-openstack-manuals-tox-checklinks/3be6a02/ : SUCCESS in 2m 48s (non-voting)

Member role was not created for me by Keystone. I will confirm it soon but I need to rewamp some things for that.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-04-16 06:26:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

It seems needed for openSUSE/SLES. Pranav, mark the step with os="opensuse;sles".

My system has:
openstack role list
+----------------------------------+-------+
| ID                               | Name  |
+----------------------------------+-------+
| a9efcdde88504bffb61b122af9c76e8f | admin |
+----------------------------------+-------+'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-04-16 06:27:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I get:

# openstack role add --project demo --user demo _member_
ERROR: openstack No role with a name or ID of '_member_' exists."}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-04-16 10:46:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Same for RedHat based distributions, I have to manually add the role there.

[vagrant@controller ~]$ openstack role add --project demo --user demo _member_
ERROR: openstack No role with a name or ID of '_member_' exists."}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-04-16 10:46:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-04-16 10:51:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-04-16 10:52:28.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-04-16 10:52:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Sorry, added os=.. to the wrong step.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-04-16 10:55:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2

Thanks!'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-16 11:08:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-openstack-manuals-tox-checklinks http://logs.openstack.org/51/173951/3/check/gate-openstack-manuals-tox-checklinks/61e71f8/ : SUCCESS in 2m 18s (non-voting)
- gate-openstack-manuals-tox-checkniceness http://logs.openstack.org/51/173951/3/check/gate-openstack-manuals-tox-checkniceness/21b0006/ : SUCCESS in 2m 18s

- gate-openstack-manuals-tox-checkdeletions http://logs.openstack.org/51/173951/3/check/gate-openstack-manuals-tox-checkdeletions/ca9e90e/ : SUCCESS in 2m 11s
- gate-openstack-manuals-tox-doc-publish-checkbuild http://docs-draft.openstack.org/51/173951/3/check/gate-openstack-manuals-tox-doc-publish-checkbuild/a204fca//publish-docs/ : SUCCESS in 11m 24s'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-04-16 14:29:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Can someone e-mail me the default keystone.conf file from SUSE and RH?'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-04-16 14:36:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

For RH: http://paste.openstack.org/show/204110/'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-04-16 14:36:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

At the moment I do not understand the problem. We have tested it on SUSE and RedHat and we have to create the role on both distributions. Why can we not merge this patch?'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-04-16 14:40:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I recall several bug reports in the Juno guide because we explicitly created a _member_ role that conflicted with the automatic _member_ role, so I want to make sure we're not going to break stuff again."}, {'account_id': 6843, 'date': '2015-04-16 15:34:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

For now I am also -1ing this patch. I have installed keystone several times from source and have never needed to add a member role. Let me find out where htis role gets added. Then we can decide how to move on.'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-04-16 16:40:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Code-Review

Upon further investigation with Phil Hopkins and Dolph Mathews, we determined that the change from assigning a default project to a user when creating the user to splitting the operation into separate steps (preferred for keystone v3) prevents automatic creation of the _member_ role. On a somewhat related note, I also learned that we should not rely on the _member_ role. However, we can address this issue in a separate patch.'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-04-16 16:41:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Also, please make this patch apply to all distributions.'}, {'account_id': 6843, 'date': '2015-04-16 17:54:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

Agree with Matt'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-04-16 18:12:11.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-04-16 18:13:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2

Thanks everybody for figuring out the right solution and providing this!'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-16 18:56:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

commit_message:
Install Guide: Fix rabbitmq-server for openSUSE/SLES

To start rabbitmq-server, epmd needs to listen on the controller IP.

I'm discussing this in bugzilla now but want to document this behaviour
so that others will not run into it.

Change-Id: I9406ed002b68e8b5c9c60b7a07a10673096a527d

The changes look very good to me. The only thing IMO that's missing is proper testing. Nikolay, please provide a test that explicitly check ordering. I would suggest we use a number of actions called multiple times using "with-items" where every action would sleep for a small random period of time (utils.random_sleep could be used when https://review.openstack.org/#/c/172389/ gets merged in). That way we would emulate random order of action results' arrival.'}, {'account_id': 7700, 'date': '2015-04-15 16:00:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Workflow-1

no-no :) std.echo would be enough to check it. commit_message:
Actually run function tests

run_tests.sh runs all scripts tests/test_* as for the upstream
unit-test job, but a lot of tests are in "functions.sh" which isn't
picked up.  The existing "test_functions.sh" is only testing
true/false function -- move that into its own sub-test (it also uses
unittest.sh functions; easier to leave it alone) and move
"functions.sh" to "test_functions.sh" so that it is run.

Also update comment in run_tests.sh, which seems to be an old
reference to when less testing was done.

Change-Id: I3f6042f1ad324fc03d45c16e8dbf95b751d62e5e

commit_message:
Add rabbitmq max_retries and retry_interval attr

Oslo.message using rabbit_max_retries and rabbit_retry_interval to
define reconnect rabbitmq server times and interval when can not
connect to rabbitmq server.

Change-Id: I6bba768f4cf0c61b92fbc5d682b60f094afb7180
Partial-bug: #1439968

commit_message:
Fix client when using no ssl compression

Since the release of the 0.16.1 client, using the 'no ssl compression'
option, whether on the command line, or via the library -- Nova does this by
default -- a stack trace was generated.

Closes-bug: 1442664
Related-bug: 1357430

Change-Id: I2b8ddcb0a7ae3cfccdfc20d3ba476f3b4f4ec32d
(cherry picked from commit c698b4e3227b4767f042e435423fcc307d7f6d5c)

commit_message:
Add SSL cert verification regression tests

A security bug (1357430) was introduced which meant that SSL certificate
verification was not occurring.

Add new tests which help prevent the 'requests' part of bug 115260
recurring.

Note: Cherry-picking onto the stable branch -- these tests are required
      for proper testing of one of the SSL related fixes.

Change-Id: Iaf56fd8bc34fa8f35c2fd7051f9f8424002352cf
Related-bug: 1357430
(cherry picked from commit 64a1a0fdcc563579a8b01d10debfafc4cc160f81)

commit_message:
Don't autodoc the test suite

Don't build API documentation for the keystone tests. These are not
public functions, pollute the existing docs, and extend the time
required to build docs.

Change-Id: I334c485af7926adc31a28ec600861b43dfc6bedc

commit_message:
Ignore non-release related tags

Previously we were accepting many string tags to be release
tags for versions.  This change enforces tags that are
considered to start with a digit, and ignore if not.

Change-Id: Ib1ca0eda62e375cdee70d35ed7c82a544082ef0a
Closes-bug: 1403124
Signed-off-by: Dave Walker (Daviey) <email@daviey.com>

commit_message:
Mask passwords with iscsiadm commands

This patch adds the fix that exists in the nova
libvirt volume code to use oslo_utils strutils
to mask passwords that might show up in debug log
messages.

Change-Id: I632eb4d71588736ab21327824d0506c13f3933ae
Closes-Bug: 1445137

commit_message:
Adding MySQL fixes to migrations

This change adds general fixes need for MySQL to perform the migrations
from stable/juno to kilo. For MySQL, the Alembic documentation
recommends adding the type to all drop_constraints calls, additionally
it is needed for alter_column as well. There is also an issue with MySQL
not allowing some alter_column changes on columns that have foreign key
constraints.

Changes
* correcting alter_column and drop_constraints in 795737bb3c3
* correcting alter_column in 256da65e0c5f
* correcting drop_constraints and associated behavior in 1c0f328bfce0
* adding names for the foreign constraints in ProjectSecret
* adding names for the foreign constraints in
  PreferredCertificateAuthorities

Change-Id: I558e5dca5d9c99150f2dceb251235e0d0a2f5a16
Closes-Bug: 1444209

commit_message:
Add schema for workflow input with default value support

Only add schemas. The schemas are needed for supporting something like:

my_wf:
  type: direct
  input:
    - param1
    - param2: 10

Partially Implements: blueprint mistral-default-input-values

Change-Id: I5891c5278b54e361b8818c96c771c0af9396607a

commit_message:
logic error in updating audited of firewall policy

firewall policy's audited attribute will be set to False
no matter what value you specify when you update it.

It's a simple logic error

Closes-Bug: #1438615
Change-Id: I2c25d5f0faa0988189d3245bbb03b3528f506073

commit_message:
Add AIO diagnostics and better gate scripts consistency

Implements extra diagnostic information for gate check failure analysis and
also appends DNS settings instead of replacing them for the AIO bootstrap.

Some extra settings are added to the DNS to try to catch edge cases for DNS
resolution. The DNS `resolv.conf` was being overwritten on every run using
google name servers however we need to add google name servers to the existing
resolver not overwrite the whole conf so a conditional was added.

The gate scripts were attempting to create a symlink to logs on every run.
While this is fine for the gate which is creates a new node on every run
the link will cause failures on recheck when doing more local testing.

The ansible log entry was being appended to the `ansible.cfg` file on every
run which should also be limited to one entry. The conditional added is
helpful when doing local testing with the gate scripts.

Closes-Bug: #1442630
Change-Id: I25aac98d7408ba32f94befea22da4471bd1697b6

commit_message:
Fixes a bug with stop script for neutron server

Previously, neutron-server was being started instead of stopped
in the stop script. This patch changes up -d to stop for the
neutron-server container.

Change-Id: I5e365c851624ca3b9d87b2cf7e3a5395ed460f89

commit_message:
doc changes to devstack overview.rst

changed to comply with doc conventions
When referring to services, use "Compute," "Image service"
and "Identity" instead of "nova," "glance," and "keystone."
Use the project names like "nova" and "keystone"
glance is officially Image service not storage
removed extra .

Change-Id: I39457c20dc2ede775fe3f3c63077133fbb6c917b

commit_message:
Allow id to be added in POSTs for all entities

This is to allow neturon-lbaas to be able to give its own ids so it
can know what id octavia is tracking.

Change-Id: Id49c7971894228fdf56189df86175fd35c6ed5ca

commit_message:
Add return response in some of Kubernetes APIs.

Currently the swagger generated code doesn't have return responses
for some of the APIs. So this patch adds the same in below listed APIs:

1. createPod
2. replacePod
3. createReplicationController
4. replaceReplicationController
5. createService
6. replaceService

Closes-bug:#1444867
Partially-Implements: blueprint python-k8sclient
Change-Id: I7a080fe8cd3fdea6ed2a8db9652034974ed90098

commit_message:
Merge console & console_output tests between v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges console & console_output functional tests.

In V2.1 os-access-ip is separate plugin where in v2 it was mixed in server
plugin itself. So os-access-ip extension is enabled to run
merged functional tests for both v2 and v2.1.

Change-Id: I249c10b9b154a374b61092f6fcbe9f3f2bff1dd3

commit_message:
Merge volume related functional tests of v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges volume related functional tests.

In v2, there were Snapshots/VolumeAttachments/VolumeAttachUpdate/Volumes,
all these are merged into this commit

Change-Id: I77413dfe88fc07e512f8bcdfabbb63e56e661f4b

commit_message:
Security tests for Consumer resources

These tests will attempt CRUD operations on Consumer resources, both
with and without (dummy) project ids, and always without valid tokens.
They should all return HTTP 401s. Fixed block comment formatting for
PEP8. Added tests to ConsumersUnauthedTestCase class, with 'security'
and 'negative' tags for all tests. Refactored test names to be in line
with rest of Barbican functional tests, and now using behaviors instead
of client calls. Cleaned up a typo in previous patch set.

Change-Id: I56f7417e11a184ebb824a4dcd31cae9cb8adfc23

commit_message:
Merge remote consoles tests between v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges remote consoles functional tests.

In V2.1 os-access-ip is separate plugin where in v2 it was mixed in server
plugin itself. So os-access-ip extension is enabled to run
merged functional tests for both v2 and v2.1.

Change-Id: I7db86f4e11a224071565fb8b3e211f670fc1292f

commit_message:
Merge server tests between v2 and v2.1

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges servers functional tests.

In V2.1 os-access-ip is separate plugin where in v2 it was mixed in server
plugin itself. So os-access-ip extension is enabled for server tests to run
merged functional tests for both v2 and v2.1.

Change-Id: I3dda5820cf8e1897c7a3895edb43bc708db9073d

commit_message:
make the devstack.localrc.example like the gate

This updates the example to give you a file that looks a lot more like
what we test in the gate, including flipping NEUTRON on with a single
flag. Just makes testing a lot simpler.

Change-Id: I66a6990fb556ae670bd433e40e65e24ab7960701

commit_message:
remove javelin1 & javelin2

javelin is obsoleted for direct use in grenade by the resource plugin
scripts, so remove the coupling and reference to it.

Change-Id: Ieaf63f0162f8d87a96058e941fb5b1f3e750dd2b

commit_message:
Add cinder modular verification

This includes a boot from volume test that includes putting state
inside a volume and ensuring that it's there later.

Depends-On: Iefbc8d06eb677740956b89e157e8c9e176a0564e

... which removes stopping of tgt service on stop_cinder

[{'created': '2014-11-24 09:21:16.000000000', 'message': "Support platform-specific requirements files

This patch adds support for choosing a requirements file, based on the
current OS, with the format 'requirements-{osname}'. This can be combined
with the current approach of choosing a requirement file based on the
Python version. The motivation for this is to replace conditional
choosing of packages inside setup.py.

Change-Id: I30c56082bb9b9bcd80128eedcef17b6beb793cf8
"}]
commit_message:
Support platform-specific requirements files

This patch adds support for choosing a requirements file, based on the
current OS, with the format 'requirements-{osname}'. This can be combined
with the current approach of choosing a requirement file based on the
Python version. The motivation for this is to replace conditional
choosing of packages inside setup.py.

Change-Id: I30c56082bb9b9bcd80128eedcef17b6beb793cf8

commit_message:
Add return vlaue judge

rc_create and service_create in kube.py  both return None
when kube_cli excute fail.The code where call the function
didn't judge the return vlaue,and use object.xx get value
that's will got "'NoneType' object has no attribute "xx"
error.

Change-Id: Ic5597b4c36031cbc342ccbc5bd1bfd10c3142025
Closes-bug:#1442453

commit_message:
do not stop tgt when we stop cinder

tgt should remain up after we stop cinder, it shouldn't go down with
it, as that prevents servers with volumes from functioning when the
control plane is down.

Change-Id: Iefbc8d06eb677740956b89e157e8c9e176a0564e

  problems on for Python-cueclient.  Specifically when updated_at
  field is returned as None and Python-cueclient tries to create

closes-bug: #1444758
'}]
commit_message:
Resolving Removing Empty fields from API responses

* Returning empty fields set to Nonw for unset fields will cause
  problems on for Python-cueclient.  Specifically when updated_at
  field is returned as None and Python-cueclient tries to create
  a datetime object from it.

Change-Id: I753d80e554ec7937d89435fcef9f89138acfb48d
closes-bug: #1444758

commit_message:
Updated nova to allow for v3 and ec2 to be enabled

The paste.ini has been rebased on upstream master and a conditional
was added to the nova.conf file.

This change makes it possible for a deployer to consume the
deprecated apis for EC2 and NovaV3. While The endpoints will not be
"automatically" created the paste config has been rebased to support
the apis if needed.

Partially implements: blueprint master-kilofication

Change-Id: I061d743b569ebc0753a47d183545ed185bad854e

commit_message:
Renamed AIO example files

The AIO example files have been renamed such that they are no longer
creating an issue where the deployer "could" cause problems in
deployment when the AIO configuration files are being used by
default. The issue is ever present when the deployer does a blind
copy of the etc/openstack_deloy directory into /etc/.

This change is to enhance the Kilo gating / deployment process.

Partially implements: blueprint master-kilofication

Change-Id: I0c76ae9012aeafcc8a39a03c0e11b68b2ee5ca9c

commit_message:
Write and read more complex git sha info

Instead of encoding the git sha into the version string, add it to
a metadata file. This will allow us to get out of the business of
arguing with pip and setuptools about version info. In order to make
this really nice, provide a command line utility called "pbr" that has
subcommands to print out the metadata that we're now including in the
egg-info dir.

(cherry picked from commit b3678714aabd9c82a4ad389036e160a0819fd45c)

Conflicts:
	pbr/packaging.py

Change-Id: I35a1489c9ab637769218d1e6a26d1115a52a7051

commit_message:
Enable Kubernetes v1beta3 API.

The v1beta3 API is not enabled by default. The kube-apiserver
process needs to run with the --runtime_config=api/v1beta3
argument.

Partially-Implements: blueprint python-k8sclient

Change-Id: I65c8966b27e4eb77bbaf34993b5c2c3eadb01302

commit_message:
osapi_compute_link_prefix should not be set by default

Correctly default osapi_compute_link_prefix to nil.
Added osapi_glance_link_prefix for completeness.
Created attributes for these for flexibility.
Updated specs to cover these and other misc keys.

Change-Id: Ic2fd79fc74dedb649b08c451ded678ac1d1ed310
Closes-Bug: #1418583

keepalives were attempted previously before the development of the ssh_retry plugin, so while I like the principle of removing a plugin that is not required, I recommend that the plugin remains in the base until we see no evidence of it being used, or we decided that the frequency of its use is so low that we don't need it"}, {'account_id': 7217, 'date': '2015-04-16 15:47:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

It should also be a separate commit because the SSH config changes are not proven to be equivalent.'}, {'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2015-04-16 16:06:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Please update this to leave the ssh_retry plugin bits as its removal is being handled by https://review.openstack.org/174376'}, {'account_id': 7217, 'date': '2015-04-16 16:06:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-04-16 16:10:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 7217, 'date': '2015-04-16 16:10:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 2556, 'date': '2015-04-16 16:23:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

My goal was not to remove the ssh_retry plugin for legal reasons. That's another issue, and if this fixes ssh connection issues then it's also solved by this, which is why the commit message had nothing to do with that concern.

Also, you changed my commit message to just say "keepalive" which implies just the TCPKeepAlive option, but the ServerAlive* options are also integral to this approach. As I detailed in IRC discussions, the only situations we should be missing with this approach are ones where the SSH daemon isn't listening yet or the networking between client and daemon isn't fully plumbed yet. In both such cases, we should be using Ansible's wait_for task module to wait on the port and SSH banner. Once a connection is established, these SSH client options should improve reliability of connection maintenance.

That was the idea and goal, which sidesteps consideration of license compatibilities and removes the continuing maintenance burden of updating ssh_retry as the Ansible bits it subclasses change over time, which I mentioned in the original commit message as well.

I'm happy to discuss these things in greater detail on IRC or email if necessary, but I wanted to make sure to clarify the intent and make sure to highlight what's now missing from the commit text.'}, {'account_id': 7217, 'date': '2015-04-16 16:30:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2015-04-16 16:37:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-04-16 16:47:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 12807, 'date': '2015-04-16 16:48:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-16 18:10:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

commit_message:
More user-friendly output for object metadata

Split out system, user and other metadata in swift-object-info. Print
every position line by line instead of raw dict representation, so it
would be easier to parse with tools such as grep.

Co-Authored-By: Ricardo Ferreira <ricardo.sff@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Kamil Rykowski <kamil.rykowski@intel.com>

Change-Id: Ia78da518c18f7e26016700aee87efb534fbd2040
Closes-Bug: #1428866

commit_message:
add nova modular resource checks

This adds nova modular service checks, including the use of the
verify_noapi phase to ensure the server doesn't go away when
nova-compute is down (which is a substantial enhancement of our
existing validation).

There is slight regression in checking multiple servers, however that
did not seem to be a bug that we actually ran into.

add our own local copy of ping_check to grenade. The version in
devstack gets diverted down a neutron path even though we actually
want to use it in a public context. We need to change that code to
work on public networks regardless of backend. Until then, we'll keep
our own copy.

Change-Id: I985ca38ef670b03802f9ad67ce19cf94cfc802ae

commit_message:
Fix Dogtag plugin to make latest functional tests pass

For generated keys, we add a field in the Dogtag metadata
"generated" to let the Dogtag plugin know to base64.b64decode()
the data when it is returned.  This will not be needed once the
Dogtag API is modified to automatically encode the stored results.

Also, corrected a check for existing encrypted data on a secret PUT
operation.  The existing check was only valid for the crypto_store plugin.

Change-Id: I4ca1d4f144eb740e6936c88a3786e91ee37d8f93

commit_message:
Revert "Add ipset element and hashsize tunables"

This reverts commit b5b919a7a3569ccb93c3d7d523c1edfaeddb7cb9.

The current ipset manager code isn't robust enough to handle
ipsets that already exist with different parameters. This reverts
the ability to change the parameters so we don't break upgrades
to Kilo.

Change-Id: I538714df52424f0502cb75daea310517d1142c42
Closes-Bug: #1444201

commit_message:
Fix KMIP Secret Store input/output

Fix KMIP Secret Store inputs and outpus.  Barbican core will pass in PEM
secrets as Base64(PEM), so the secret store has to convert them to DER
for use.  On secret retrieval the secret store is expected to return
Base64(PEM) back to Barbican, so we need to convert the DER coming back
from the KMIP device into a PEM.

Change-Id: I79693be16fb6ab3b781d6f215daf30274fc8200e

commit_message:
Fix stopping neutron server

`tools/stop` script introduced in
I85b31396c2b816b89f33206443c3d60cb4b7914b suffered from a bad copy
& paste and was starting neutron server container instead of stopping it.

Also cleanup comment at the top of the script to reveal its true
purpose.

Change-Id: Iea00b5b25482cc551cb4c40600f3f3cf7adafd37

commit_message:
Adds a Remove Script

Previously, you could start/stop Kolla containers but you could
not remove containers. This patch adds a script that simply
calls docker-compose rm for each Kolla container.

Change-Id: I20bc29f0cb3f4a4eea2eba26812e52aaec40c860

commit_message:
Fixes script conditions for Linux Bridge/OVS

Makes sure the scripts are checking if linuxbridge within
mech/ type drivers. Previsouly a . was missing at the end
of linuxbridge/ovs for some of the nova/neutron shell scripts.

Change-Id: I13cd0dde8791ed5f87a9dd577d284796f2a9a524

commit_message:
Add network support to the accounts providers

This commits adds support for specifying the network to use with a
user/tenant into the accounts.yaml file. You can only specify a single
network which will be the network used for all that requires a
pre-existing network. This also means regardless of which cred provider
is configured the fixed_network can assume a TestResource object will
be returned from a get_creds call. As part of this change a common
method to return the full network dict from a just a network name is
abstracted out into tempest.common.fixed_network module since this
same method is needed to have the accounts file provide a network by
name.

Partially-implements: bp test-accounts-continued
Change-Id: I6f5ac1239d18f2935847b385a08de608f40fdda5

commit_message:
add neutron resource isolation script

This simply does an create of a default shared network so that other
tests can pass in a neutron environment. Eventually it may want to
support more advanced scenarios.

Change-Id: I9d91db8c1b8910d579b0f57103b55b5134805d00

commit_message:
Use identity_uri_transform for identiry_uri support

Remove deprecated keys and use identity_uri via the new transform
helper method.

Also, cleanup specs for endpoint testing to make sure Common is
fully tested.

Change-Id: Iad3da2be74823b8d706eb9b4e12311cbf655ab7f
Implements: blueprint identity-uri

commit_message:
Enable config_drive_format parameter for nova

After this patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/133919/ has been
merged, we can do live-migration with the vfat config drive now.

This patch enable config_drive_format parameter for this purpose.

Change-Id: I3bb25d48bb8882ad898304b61d52fa2a75c2101b

commit_message:
Remove api-paste.ini as it provided by package

Since we have no attribute overrides for api-paste.ini, no
need to have a template resource for it.  Until we need to
have some attribute, removing this will take away burden of
keeping in sync with base openstack code.

Change-Id: I918b3dfc3d17fe122300d32d678addbf828df771
Related-Bug: #1433152

commit_message:
Update swarm template for latest atomic image

* Docker service needs to listen on file descriptor to work with
  systemd socket activation.
* Need to delete /etc/docker/key.json so that each host generates
  it's own unique id.
* Use smaller swarm image for agent and manager services
* Disable selinux so that cloud-init works

Closes-bug: #1444714

Change-Id: I496330af656d488b826028cec9b5d5275a63d3b4

commit_message:
Allow mq setup for keystone

In some cases, keystone notifications are required. This
Add identity to the list of component that could use messaging.

Another patch to identity will update the keystone.conf
template to make use of mq just like the other cookbooks do.

Change-Id: Id4a777e1fae53cd5ac48b860e4ac01a4e70be7e7
Partial-Bug: #1439306

And from reading this: https://github.com/sethvargo/chefspec#testing-lwrps looks like the stuff done inside the lwrp mysql_confg, should NOT be exposed and tested from another cookbook.

So, I think the best we can do here is make sure the attr defaults are correct in the default file and move on.'}, {'account_id': 15765, 'date': '2015-03-31 22:36:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 15765, 'date': '2015-03-31 22:38:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Workflow-1

I took the suggestions and fixed the gating issues. However, there are still issues with this.

I have a better understanding of what's going on here but I don't see how we can test the contents of this file since as you pointed out, the resource is an LWRP (mysql_config) from another cookbook (mysql).

      it 'has valid mysql openstack options set' do
        [/^default-storage-engine = InnoDB$/,
          ...
         /^max_connections = 1024$/].each do |line|
          expect(chef_run).to render_config_file(file)\
            .with_section_content('mysqld', line)

I can successfully get the above to work if file is the result of a standard template resource, but it doesn't work if file is the result of an LWRP like mysql_config since the resource doesn't actually exist.  Quoting from the ChefSpec docs:

"ChefSpec overrides all providers to take no action (otherwise it would actually converge your system). This means that the steps inside your LWRP are not actually executed. If an LWRP performs actions, those actions are never executed or added to the resource collection."

It does on to say the normal way to test this is to step into the LWRP, but as you pointed out, never to do this if the LWRP is from another cookbook.

Later in the documentation (and also here: https://github.com/sethvargo/chefspec/issues/530), he describes how testing LWRPs from other cookbooks should be handled and it includes adding a custom matcher in the cookbook where the LWRP resides.

In order to test this, it seems we would need something similar to the render_config_file().with_section_content to be added to the mysql cookbook and have a matcher that exposes it for testing outside that cookbook.

Please let me know if I am misunderstand anything or if you have any other suggestions.'}, {'account_id': 15765, 'date': '2015-03-31 22:44:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Add additional mysql tunables

Adding more mysql tuning options to better support production-like
environments. These additional attribues have been set to default
values that match the mysql defaults. Including spec tests.

Change-Id: Iadb0746354ea93a6beef9ecbae5d1bdc5cec1d48
Closes-Bug: #1436481

commit_message:
Updates service and config for Octavia API

Updates bind_port default to something not already used(hopefully)
Updates prepare_service to follow oslo_log new behaviour
Updates octavia.conf bind_port default

Change-Id: I399aeb200bccb97ada4e8d59ac7b3ffb0646fb6d

Transaction and BaseCommand classes will be used from OVS_LIB (Terrys work) code for reuse, they are still missing some small additions that i sent in reviews: (thats why they are used here as well)
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/170842/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/170771/

I posted it so others can take a look, this is still not done and not attached.

If you want to test it, need to:
1) add /opt/stack/ovs/python  to PYTHONPATH (for OVS IDL)
2) change in the mech driver the _ovn implementation class to use the IDL
3) add this to mech driver init : self.vsctl_timeout = 10

(I will work on removing all the above dependencies soon)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-07 06:23:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Update to pull in 3.x versions of the rabbitmq cookbook

Several fixes and minor enhancements have gone into the rabbitmq
cookbook.  This change allows all 3.12 < 4.0 minors to be picked up.

Change-Id: Ica9f4f5165d6c566bd0bddbf35e66fb5412cf987

[{'created': '2015-04-07 10:44:11.000000000', 'message': 'Loadbalancer: Add support for Redis

commit_message:
Loadbalancer: Add support for Redis

Add support for Redis in the loadbalancer setup.
Redis loadbalancing system is particular as it does not provide
clustering capabilities yet, hence this pattern[1] will be applied.

[1] https://github.com/falsecz/haredis

Change-Id: I80a6c284af9eceb6b669a03c5d93256261523331

commit_message:
Added script to facilitate juno to kilo upgrade

This script was created to allow for Juno (v10.x) to be
upgrade to Kilo (v11.x). This script attempts to wrap all
of the changes that have taken place between the Rackspace
release of Juno and the community product created in master
that is Kilo.

Partially implements: blueprint master-kilofication

Change-Id: Ibbc2a8192fb3a4e8508aefc74b1d062cd890f1a0

commit_message:
Remove ssh_retry plugin.

It has been decided that this plugin should be GPL licesnsed, and is
therefore incompatible with OSAD's Apache License.

Removing to keep OSAD GPL free.

Change-Id: Ifc28bb38f0d0a8fc5096ec06c975ee19a4e60374

commit_message:
Managing policy file with default file and user variables.

Currently, the default policy.json files for all projects are just
dropped into place. There is no flexibility to customize, edit or update
certain key-values in the policy.json. This change adds a custom module
called 'copy_updates' that allows any updates to be applied to the
default file.

Implements: blueprint dynamically-manage-policy.json
Change-Id: Iadaaeb935f4602835b1cec858b53d4db8c18b1b0

commit_message:
Deployment related cleanup

- Changing assembly status to correctly reflect failure
  to create an assembly
- Reordering setting of assembly status and uploading of
  tenant's deployer log
- Removing tenant-id from location of tenant's deployer
  logs. This is to be consistent with how we are naming
  logs for unittest and build stages.

Co-Authored-By: Ed Cranford <ed.cranford@rackspace.com>
Change-Id: I98af988ad9726513127f4478d47f26f050e639c7

commit_message:
Fix best response to return correct status

Current best response could return "503 Internal Server Error".
However, "503" means "Service Unavailable". (The status int of
Internal Server Error is 500)

This patch fixes the response status as "503 Service Unavailable"

Change-Id: I88b8c52c26b19e9e76ba3375f1e16ced555ed54c

I am not sure glance-api and glance-registry can sit on different nodes:

init_glance is the function that (re)creates the SQL database. Currently init_glance is called when g-reg is enabled. So if you have glance-api and glance-registry on different nodes and the node with g-api starts first, you will run into issue because the SQL DB will not be there.'}, {'account_id': 13998, 'date': '2015-04-11 16:59:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

What I tried to do was to install a multi-node setup as explained in the readme.
In this setup I have one controller node, which runs glance-registry and glance-api, and a compute node which only runs glance-api. The glance-api on the compute node uses the glance-registry on the controller node (at least thats how I understand it).
It is clear that I have to start the glance-registry on the controller node before I can start the glance-api on the compute node, but even after glance-registry has started, glance-api will not start on the compute node because the glance cache directory is not there (it only gets created on the controller node when glance-registry starts).
So what I try to do in this patch is to create the glance cache directory when glance-api is enabled but glance-registry is not.'}, {'account_id': 13998, 'date': '2015-04-13 09:27:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Ok, I just did some testing and it looks like a compute node does not even need the glance-api service to be enabled.

This makes my fix rather irrelevant, as it seems like this is just a problem in the documentation of the multi-node setup.

I will just overwrite my patch with a fix for the readme.'}, {'account_id': 13998, 'date': '2015-04-13 09:33:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-13 10:34:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1
