[{'created': '2015-04-07 14:55:32.000000000', 'message': 'Create glance cache dir when g-reg is disabled

Create the glance cache directory when g-reg is disabled
but g-api is enabled (for example in a multi-node setup).
Not creating the cache directory leads to g-api crashing
on startup because it can not create the cache on its own.

Change-Id: Ie92533f3333f3fe3e2d747762e60f2f42a233e79
Closes-bug: #1441198
'}, {'created': '2015-04-13 09:33:15.000000000', 'message': 'Fix readme for multi-node setup

The readme stated that a compute node in a multi-node setup requires the
glance-api service to be enabled. But actually the glance-api service is only
required on the controller node where glance-registry is running.
Running the glance-api service on a node without glance-registry will even lead
to a failure of glance-api, as the glance cache directory will not be created

commit_message:
Fix readme for multi-node setup

The readme currently states that a compute node in a multi-node setup
requires the glance-api service to be enabled. But actually
the glance-api service is only required on the controller node where
glance-registry is running.
Running the glance-api service on a node without glance-registry will
even lead to a failure of glance-api, as the glance cache directory
will not be created without enabling glance-registry.

Change-Id: Ie92533f3333f3fe3e2d747762e60f2f42a233e79
Closes-bug: #1441198

commit_message:
Fix always false condition in glance wrapper

If statement's condition in GlanceClientWrapper's method 'call'
always false, because 'version' key passed through kwargs is
string, and variable chacked in 'call' is None or int.

Change-Id: Ief1e8d2c41aaa774666bc59d63cdea68f80f308a
Closes-Bug: #1439275

commit_message:
Perform Neutron actions based on target

1) Only generate neutron configuration files necessary for
   each target.
2) Limit database connection string in neutron.conf to server
   container.
3) Limit database sync to neutron server container.

Co-Authored-By: Matt Kassawara <mkassawara@gmail.com>
Change-Id: Iba8903235675dec4e7bf6b01eeb130f7b43bbfef
Closes-Bug: 1443927

When a heat stack is created and we are waiting for a docker image
to be pulled and run, we put the app in the 'WAITING_FOR_DOCKER_DU'

commit_message:
Change 'waiting_for_docker_du' state

When a heat stack is created and we are waiting for a docker image
to be pulled and run, we put the app in the 'WAITING_FOR_DOCKER_DU'
 state.

This name does not make sense to end users.

I propose we change it to 'STARTING_APP'

Change-Id: Ib5264661c4cb2410109a68f07cff188736dc3413
Closes-bug: 1444678

commit_message:
Potential resource exhaustion when registering consumers to containers

Previously, it was possible for consumers to be added with names of
arbitrary length. According to a finding by the Rackspace security
team, this ended up being a bigger problem than previously thought given
that addition of such consumers with sufficiently long names was apt to crash the running Barbican
instance.
Closes-Bug: 1430516

Change-Id: Ia5114d8de7dec796c56060892f389e47140c7834

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-20 15:12:56.000000000', 'message': 'Ignore HTTP_PROXY during test requests

urllib2 follows http_proxy/HTTP_PROXY by default.  If a (non-local)
proxy is set and a test tries to connect to localhost:$port, it will
instead attempt to connect to $port on the proxy and (presumably) fail.

This change forces the two tests that failed in the presence of
HTTP_PROXY to connect directly.

(cherry picked from commit b0ebfb90958afac39be24b5157763d479256ab8c)
Change-Id: Ia12c91b356f0ccebf874933ff459aa2faa190655

Deal with PEP-0476 certificate chaining checking

PEP-0476 introduced more thorough certificate chain verfication
for HTTPS connectivity; this was introduced in Python 2.7.9, and
breaks a number of unit tests in the cinder codebase.

Disable certificate chain verification for cinder SSL tests
using the backwards compatible SSLContext provided for this
purpose.

Closes-Bug: #1403068

Conflicts:
	cinder/tests/test_wsgi.py

(cherry picked from commit 4e849ef5fbb7159276435ac6f7315bf20274768d)
Change-Id: Iffc3658196f608c7a7c9b6527dc8e7210fb05bff

commit_message:
Deal with PEP-0476 certificate chaining checking

PEP-0476 introduced more thorough certificate chain verfication
for HTTPS connectivity; this was introduced in Python 2.7.9, and
breaks a number of unit tests in the cinder codebase.

Disable certificate chain verification for cinder SSL tests
using the backwards compatible SSLContext provided for this
purpose.

Closes-Bug: #1403068
(cherry picked from commit 4e849ef5fbb7159276435ac6f7315bf20274768d)

Conflicts:
	cinder/tests/test_wsgi.py

Change-Id: Iffc3658196f608c7a7c9b6527dc8e7210fb05bff

commit_message:
Ignore HTTP_PROXY during test requests

urllib2 follows http_proxy/HTTP_PROXY by default.  If a (non-local)
proxy is set and a test tries to connect to localhost:$port, it will
instead attempt to connect to $port on the proxy and (presumably) fail.

This change forces the two tests that failed in the presence of
HTTP_PROXY to connect directly.

Change-Id: Ia12c91b356f0ccebf874933ff459aa2faa190655
(cherry picked from commit b0ebfb90958afac39be24b5157763d479256ab8c)

Hi Matt. This looks good. I am wondering how much work it will be to maintain it though :-( I think it is useful (for at least some of these options) if the descriptions were more verbose than we have in the comments. I wonder if it might be easier for us in the long run, to update the .sample and use that as documentation.

My goal was to try to have documentation that had content similar to http://docs.openstack.org/havana/config-reference/content/ch_configuring-openstack-compute.html. So that some doc writer later could transform the info into whatever desired format:-)

Thanks, Ruby. That's exactly the type of feedback I was looking for.

I agree about the need for documenting sample configs. My thinking was to have two documents; one outlining all options, and one giving some documentation for how to set up various things. I think combining them in one document would be too heavy, though -- this thing is already 800 lines.

I also agree about trying to expand on what's in the comments, but that's a pretty hefty undertaking. My thinking -- and I'm interested in if others agree -- was to start with what's in the comments (with a bit of cleanup) and then gradually expand.

I'm left wondering overall how much value is in this, or if it makes sense to try to just automate this. I think there's something to be said for trying to have something more polished, but I agree with your questions about maintainability."}, {'account_id': 10342, 'date': '2014-04-03 19:40:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Is there any reason the config documentation shouldn't be fully contained within the automatically generated config? It seems like if we're missing good documentation of behavior and defaults, we should update the descriptions in the code so the better documentation comes all the way through.

Perhaps, even, if we felt it neccessary, we could generate a document similar to what you've proposed here except automatically from the same methods used to generate the config file. Overall though, maintaining a separate document for the config file in parallel seems highly likely to end up unsynchronized and confuse people."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2014-04-11 06:03:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Use openstack CLI instead of keystone

When running './stack.sh' messages are output stating that
the keystone CLI has been deprecated. These calls should be
replaced to ones utilizing the openstack CLI program instead.

Documentation examples were also updated to reflect the new syntax.

Change-Id: Ib20b8940e317d150e5f6febb618e20bd85d13f8b
Closes-Bug: #1441340

clean.sh picks the parent of LOGFILE and wipes it clean! So if you

commit_message:
Setting LOGFILE to a file in root directory wipes everything

clean.sh picks the parent of LOGFILE and wipes it clean! So if you
set it to a log file in the users root directory, you lose everything

We should delete just the LOGFILE and cleanup LOGDIR and SCREEN_LOGDIR if
they are explicitly set.

Change-Id: I45745427dcaed3dcf0b78cc9ed680833d9d555e8

commit_message:
Recap ceilometerclient for stable/icehouse

ceilometerclient's stable/icehouse branch has 1.0.12, and since the
requirement was <=1.0.12 we can't create patches since they get
a version like 1.0.12.post1

Change-Id: Ic27aa88085656298a91001f9a95686d3031ea7ac

commit_message:
Add support for arm64 images

This patch enables proper support for arm64 images by disabling VNC support
and adding several properties to the image in glance that are necessary to
boot correctly:
  hw_cdrom_bus=virtio
  hw_machine_type=virt
  os_command_line='console=ttyAMA0'

Change-Id: I68c9a5e0e083af2f92875c3bdf70df750f6e4d8f

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-15 23:03:18.000000000', 'message': 'LPAR-specific SSP ops target VIOSes on same host

When nova is managing an SSP Cluster whose VIOSes span multiple
accessible hosts (e.g. nova is running against a single HMC managing
multiple hosts), it is important that operations specific to a
particular instance - such as creating and removing disk connections -
be invoked only on the VIOS(es) residing on the same host as that
instance.  This change set fixes the SSP Disk Driver to ensure this is
the case.

Ancillary to this change is an expansion and refactoring of the vm
utility to retrieve quick properties for an LPAR.  Invoking the new
vm.get_vm_qp method without the qprop parameter will return a dictionary
of all the quick properties available for the LPAR.

Change-Id: Ib1d02743baf041c9abc69b25201d33e516fa6cb3

commit_message:
LPAR-specific SSP ops target VIOSes on same host

When nova is managing an SSP Cluster whose VIOSes span multiple
accessible hosts (e.g. nova is running against a single HMC managing
multiple hosts), it is important that operations specific to a
particular instance - such as creating and removing disk connections -
be invoked only on the VIOS(es) residing on the same host as that
instance.  This change set fixes the SSP Disk Driver to ensure this is
the case.

Ancillary to this change is an expansion and refactoring of the vm
utility to retrieve quick properties for an LPAR.  Invoking the new
vm.get_vm_qp method without the qprop parameter will return a dictionary
of all the quick properties available for the LPAR.

Change-Id: Ib1d02743baf041c9abc69b25201d33e516fa6cb3

commit_message:
Replace httplib with requests in the http store

By replacing Httplib with requests we forward most of
HTTP heavy lifting to a well tested library and in the same
time we gain new feature like proxy awareness in case glance
was deployed behind a proxy.

commit_message:
print user friendly error message for alarm update time constraints

Currently, if we update an alarm with wrong time constraint which
doesn't get name defined, then the shell only prints a very simple
string 'name'.

This is because our code assume name field has always been specified,
however it is not true, then KeyError exception will be raised but not
handled well, finally user only gets an implicit message.

This patch uses dict.get() for name field, and sends request (may be broken)
to ceilometer api, then extracts error message from response.

Change-Id: I086c4ec790acc22767ba7f5e43dbcf73f3af5dff
Closes-Bug: #1439207

commit_message:
Improve logging in fixed_networks

This commit makes some logging improvements to the common methods in
fixed_networks.py. Previously it was very difficult to trace through
any issues around network selection since it only would log the final
result and on failures. It also didn't attribute any messages to the
tests making the call. This fixes both issues by first leveraging
find_test_caller() from tempest-lib to get the test caller name and
secondly add more logging to help trace through the logic if something
fails. Additionally as part of this it was necessary to add additional
checks to the logic to ensure the logging was accurate and things were
in a known state.

Change-Id: Ifef67ed4578f48d7701635e7d81c144dc28b6120

commit_message:
Check to see if instance kwarg is a string

The instance_format config option needs a uuid kwarg for formatting but
the instance kwarg value can be a string uuid or instance dict/object
which contains a 'uuid' key/attribute.

Update the code to handle the instance_format config option formatting
for both string and dict/object values.

Closes-Bug: #1444728

Change-Id: I177de104bfeaee6c0769d5c0c02f32fa7bc3f12c

commit_message:
Move ComputeNode creation at init stage in ResourceTracker

This is the first step in a series refactoring code that uses
ResourceTracker.compute_node so that it can later be changed
to be a ComputeNode object. Note that in this patch compute_node
is still a dict.

The main refactor in this patch is to move initialization of the
compute_node property to a new method called _init_compute_node()
That is called near the beginning of update_available_resource().

At the moment the update methods use a method parameter called
resources that is either the resources data structure obtained from
the virt driver or the compute_node property, depending on how it is
called. The result is always copied into the compute_node property.
This change initialises the compute_node property and creates the
compute node record as an initialisation step.

Moving the initialization of the compute_node property to the start
of update_available_resources() paves the way for the next patch in
this series to use it consistently in the update methods. The
code will then be ready to introduce the ComputeNode object.

This patch also fixes bug 1415768

Co-Authored-By: Sylvain Bauza <sbauza@redhat.com>
Co-Authored-By: Ed Leafe <ed@leafe.com>

(cherry picked from commit c3ffcd18d9fb1d999d6fa360a811b4c7fdcaba13)

Conflicts:
	nova/compute/resource_tracker.py
	nova/tests/pci/test_pci_manager.py
	nova/tests/unit/compute/test_tracker.py

Closes-bug #1415768
Closes-bug #1383465

Change-Id: Ic04af76c3835a5bf63a42163d0335d6c7e26d68a

commit_message:
Disable syncs to libs to unjam master requirements changes

We need to disable syncs and checks of requirements in libraries so we
can release updated versions of all libs that have no capped
requirements. We can restore the syncs when that is done, and then we'll
look into ways to update the tools to not update caps on library
projects.

http://logs.openstack.org/24/173924/1/check/check-tempest-dsvm-full/6c09e06/logs/devstacklog.txt.gz#_2015-04-15_23_02_58_575

Change-Id: Ib948b756b8e6ca47a4c9c44c48031e54b7386a06

commit_message:
Add utility functions to convert between and PEM and DER

Adding utility routines to convert the format of public and private
keys between PEM and DER format, using only the pyOpenSSL and pyCrypto libraries.
These routines support PKCS#8.  The unit tests verify that the inputs and
outputs are identical with the equivalent openssl cli commands.

Change-Id: I27480088a5c441e1d2e66354cc08e9a27d7c3f18

commit_message:
Fix handling of payload_content_encoding for orders

The Barbican API defines three payload related fields:
   payload: the data in the current message
   payload_content_type: optional, but required if there is a payload
   payload_content_encoding: optional, but required if the type requires it

None of the three current order types use payload as an input.
Therefore, orders that include a payload should fail.  For valid orders,
payload_content_type and payload_content_encoding, if included, are
meaningless and can be ignored.

This commit:
   Adds checks to validate that orders do not send a payload,
   Removes the checks that previously required or validated,
        payload_content_encoding, and
   Updates the test cases accordingly.

Closes-bug: #1443058
Change-Id: I3cfee14bc51060100f300de292648f5477a4adb5

commit_message:
compute: stop handling virt lifecycle events in cleanup_host()

When rebooting a compute host, guest VMs can be getting shutdown
automatically by the hypervisor and the virt driver is sending events to
the compute manager to handle them. If the compute service is still up
while this happens it will try to call the stop API to power off the
instance and update the database to show the instance as stopped.

When the compute service comes back up and events come in from the virt
driver that the guest VMs are running, nova will see that the vm_state
on the instance in the nova database is STOPPED and shut down the
instance by calling the stop API (basically ignoring what the virt
driver / hypervisor tells nova is the state of the guest VM).

Alternatively, if the compute service shuts down after changing the
intance task_state to 'powering-off' but before the stop API cast is
complete, the instance can be in a strange vm_state/task_state
combination that requires the admin to manually reset the task_state to
recover the instance.

Let's just try to avoid some of this mess by disconnecting the event
handling when the compute service is shutting down like we do for
neutron VIF plugging events. There could still be races here if the
compute service is shutting down after the hypervisor (e.g. libvirtd),
but this is at least a best attempt to do the mitigate the potential
damage.

Closes-Bug: #1444630
Related-Bug: #1293480
Related-Bug: #1408176

Change-Id: I1a321371dff7933cdd11d31d9f9c2a2f850fd8d9

commit_message:
Clean up unused stable-compat jobs configuration

Neither the stable-compat job group nor the templates they define
are used any longer, so remove them any any instantiations thereof.
Also remove a stray voting override for one of these jobs left
behind in the zuul layout.

Change-Id: Ia40d8cbf8cef803617509aeca20a9f1ec79d0880

commit_message:
process: add new section History

History are used to make easy users to follow the
evolution of the spec.

The spec can differ with the time, and the design can be updated
it should be important for users who use the spec has a documentation
to see those changes without to use a third tool.

The initial proposal is to add an entry for each update provided to
the spec (even fixing a typo) but we can restrain it only for changes
in the design or new contributor refered...

Change-Id: I13b8e09d5d7848ee4657214a86d2b48bf1b05e2a

commit_message:
Fix base64 decoding of payloads in one-step POST

Fix the way that normalization was handling base64 encoding in a
one-step POST secret creation.

Previous to this CR, PEM payloads in a one-step POST with
payload_content_encoding="base64" were being converted to DER form,
which was inconsistent with the way content-encoding works with other
secret types.

This CR requires that PEM payloads be base64 encoded in their entirety
to be included in a one-step POST.

This also means that when a PEM payload is passed to the secret_store it
will be base64 encoded in its entirety, so secret stores that need to
use DER forms need to make the conversion internally in the plugin.
I will add the changes for the KMIP secret store in a follow-up CR.

Barbican core also expects PEM formatted payloads that have been base64
encoded back from the secret_store during a get, so those changes are
made as well.

Fixes-Bug: #1441866
Change-Id: Ifbe021729a14f18fddd05991f6f96e49fbcf5c01
Co-Authored-By: Dave McCowan <dmccowan@cisco.com>

commit_message:
FWaaS: Remove check for bash usage

Like Neutron, removing the check for bash script usage and
changed bash scripts to use '#!/usr/bin/env bash'.

Change-Id: Id0a74c1a976c06c66ebb370d0d9e17de17dc5231
Closes-Bug: #1441632

commit_message:
WIP Searchable index service PoC

This is a POC of using the glance search catalog.
It is only intended for providing a quick demo of the search
possibilities.

Change-Id: I8a5b18759caac6fd48c0e2ad65a42378130c446e

commit_message:
[install-guide] [yum] install libvirt-daemon-kvm before starting libvirtd

Before starting the libvirtd service it is necessary to install the
libvirt-daemon-kvm package. Libvirt is not installed as a dependency of
openstack-nova-compute.

Partially implements bp installguide-kilo.

Change-Id: I530da649ad806a4ac3e578d1e8f542b547c41539

commit_message:
Fix rebuild of an instance with a volume attached

When detaching block devices on rebuild we only notify Cinder it's
safe to detach a volume, but don't actually tell the driver to do
that first.

Closes-Bug: #1440762

Change-Id: I017bf749f426717dc76cf99a387102848fb1c541

commit_message:
let fake virt track resources

For building scheduling test cases we need the fake virt driver to
actually track the allocated resources to trigger scheduler out of
resource logic. This provides a simple allocator / deallocator model
for that.

(cherry picked from commit e6cbfa33f3ebde617d5bdba39bd44eb9c528ce92)

Conflicts:
	nova/virt/fake.py

Partial-bug #1383465 (relevant to Juno only)
Change-Id: Ifa006f70b9bbb0c0b2a5db066e1ba87aa1b50b34

In an effort to improve people's awareness of security, I'm trying to get away from putting passwords on command lines."}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-04-15 15:03:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

It should be mentioned that it should not be used in a production environments. At the moment we also paste the passwords for RabbitMQ and MySQL and I think it is nice to be able to copy & paste as much as possible.'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2015-04-15 15:17:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm worried that if we provide two commands with two slightly different outputs, people will try to run both of them. So, we either go with the version that includes the password on the command line or the one that doesn't include it... and then make the change globally. Frankly, this issue is nit-picky and could wait until after the installation guide works for Kilo."}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-04-15 15:26:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-04-16 16:14:32.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

commit_message:
[install-guide] make creation of Keystone user copy & paste compatible

Note that it is possible to prompt for the password when creating a new
Keystone user and add instructions that directly be used to create a new
Keystone user.

commit_message:
Pin puppetlabs-concat to 1.2.1 in fixtures

Puppet Labs is in the process of releasing a 2.0.0 version of
puppetlabs-concat, which will have many breaking changes that affect
many dependent modules. Changes have been merged to master, but not yet
released. While we figure out what changes we need to make in our own
modules and wait for updates in dependent modules, we should just pin
to a stable version.

Change-Id: Ifb4ca49a9dcbeb3b20781ed24ecd16ae9348903b
(cherry picked from commit 2737af141ac88a07cda39e402dacb4275792aa8f)

I have some comments and questions inline. My bigger concerns are

- This will only work for keystone providers since none of the changes were made to the Puppet::Provider::Openstack class. This change makes it so things can only be managed when authing with a token instead of a username/password. I think work needs to be done in openstacklib to make it so the provider can auth with username/password/domain.

- When running on a clean system I'm finding that the _member_ role never gets created, which causes problems in my deployment. I don't know why this is.

- I would like the spec for this to be finished, merged, and published before we merge this.

- There are a lot of irrelevant changes that make this change bigger and harder to review."}, {'account_id': 9983, 'date': '2015-03-28 21:23:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 20:

>> This will only work for keystone providers since none of the changes were made to the Puppet::Provider::Openstack class. This change makes it so things can only be managed when authing with a token instead of a username/password. I think work needs to be done in openstacklib to make it so the provider can auth with username/password/domain.

> I'm not sure what you mean. I thought I made all of my changes such that the authentication parameters provided with resource[:auth] were always used?

No, authing with username/password credentials does not work because you also need to specify a domain to auth against in order to use v3 features. There's been no change made in Puppet::Provider::Openstack to make this work.

'}, {'created': '2015-03-03 19:20:08.000000000', 'message': 'support for keystone v3 api

This is based on the blueprint:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/150108/

With keystone v3, user and project resources have to be domain aware.
When using the v3 api (either a url which ends in /v3, or using
--os-identity-api-version 3), with the openstack client,
you must either:
1) Specify the domain using the --domain argument.  You may specify
either a name or an ID.  The openstack client will do a search to
lookup the ID given a name, so if you know the ID you can save a round
trip.  This is especially required for create e.g.
 openstack user create name --domain domain
Users and projects exist inside domains.  You cannot create a user or
a project without specifying the domain that it is in.
2) Use the user and project ID instead of the name.  With keystone v3,
IDs are global - they uniquely identify resources.  You cannot have
two users in different domains with the same ID.

In puppet, resource names/titles must be unique.  In order to make user
and project resources unique and specify the domain at the same time,
the delimiter "::" has been introduced.  For example:
 keystone_user { "username::domainname" }
specifies a user in a domain.  Same with keystone_tenant and
keystone_user_role.  For keystone_user_role, since keystone v3 allows
you to create a role on a domain, there is a special syntax:
 keystone_user_role { "username::userdomain@::roledomain" }
Note that to the left of roledomain there is no project name.  This means
it is just a domain name, and the role should be assigned on the domain
rather than on a project.
For resources which also have a domain parameter, the domain parameter
will override a domain given in a resource name.
Change-Id: Iaf25d6e5e24674763918b543e705a60f26ff4e1a

For resources which also have a domain parameter, the domain parameter

There is a hidden "backdoor" way to specify the default domain to use
when installing on a non-keystone system and there is no access to the
default_domain_id in keystone.conf.  Create the file /tmp/.domain like this:

[DEFAULT]

you must either:

either a name or an ID.  The openstack client will do a search to
lookup the ID given a name, so if you know the ID you can save a round
trip.  This is especially required for create e.g.

Users and projects exist inside domains.  You cannot create a user or
a project without specifying the domain that it is in.

IDs are global - they uniquely identify resources.  You cannot have
two users in different domains with the same ID.

In puppet, resource names/titles must be unique.  In order to make user
and project resources unique and specify the domain at the same time,
the delimiter "::" has been introduced.  For example:
 keystone_user { "username::domainname" }
specifies a user in a domain.  Same with keystone_tenant and
keystone_user_role.  For keystone_user_role, since keystone v3 allows
you to create a role on a domain, there is a special syntax:
 keystone_user_role { "username::userdomain@::roledomain" }

it is just a domain name, and the role should be assigned on the domain
rather than on a project.

will override a domain given in a resource name.

when installing on a non-keystone system and there is no access to the
default_domain_id in keystone.conf.  Create the file /tmp/.domain like this:

[DEFAULT]
default_domain_name=Default
default_domain_id=default

or use whatever your actual default domain name and id are.

commit_message:
support for keystone v3 api

Implements: blueprint api-v3-support

With keystone v3, user and project resources have to be domain aware.
When using the v3 api (either a url which ends in /v3, or using
--os-identity-api-version 3), with the openstack client,
you must either:
1) Specify the domain using the --domain argument.  You may specify
either a name or an ID.  The openstack client will do a search to
lookup the ID given a name, so if you know the ID you can save a round
trip.  This is especially required for create e.g.
 openstack user create name --domain domain
Users and projects exist inside domains.  You cannot create a user or
a project without specifying the domain that it is in.
2) Use the user and project ID instead of the name.  With keystone v3,
IDs are global - they uniquely identify resources.  You cannot have
two users in different domains with the same ID.

In puppet, resource names/titles must be unique.  In order to make user
and project resources unique and specify the domain at the same time,
the delimiter "::" has been introduced.  For example:
 keystone_user { "username::domainname" }
specifies a user in a domain.  Same with keystone_tenant and
keystone_user_role.  For keystone_user_role, since keystone v3 allows
you to create a role on a domain, there is a special syntax:
 keystone_user_role { "username::userdomain@::roledomain" }
Note that to the left of roledomain there is no project name.  This means
it is just a domain name, and the role should be assigned on the domain
rather than on a project.
For resources which also have a domain parameter, the domain parameter
will override a domain given in a resource name.

There is a hidden "backdoor" way to specify the default domain to use
when installing on a non-keystone system and there is no access to the
default_domain_id in keystone.conf.  Create the file /tmp/.domain like this:

[DEFAULT]
default_domain_name=Default
default_domain_id=default

or use whatever your actual default domain name and id are.

Change-Id: Iaf25d6e5e24674763918b543e705a60f26ff4e1a

commit_message:
Sync latest _i18n module for os_brick

The _i18n module in os_brick is out of date.
It is still using the old oslo.i18n namespace
for the i18n library instead of oslo_i18n.

This patch syncs in the latest incubator code to
correct that.

Current HEAD in OSLO:
---------------------
commit:  9117130d7e73a18f0720ecb264a0a85aa26d3816
Date:  Fri Apr 10 11:39:29 2015 +0200
Test loopingcall and threadgroup on Python 3

Changes merged with this patch:
--------------------------------
0cc741a9 - switch to oslo_i18n

Change-Id: I76d1b2449c75fbd7a4a38bffdbdf492c98f639b1

commit_message:
Shuffle of the order of BIND9 masters

Make sure that the masters given to BIND9 on an addzone are shuffled
so that different MiniDNS instances are targetted for AXFRs for different
zones

Change-Id: Id01815f8d70fa50e83f0c6bee52894b885788e49
Closes-Bug: 1444414

commit_message:
Fix for API job post bug

* previous patch broke job being posted to job board backend
  from the API
* Removing new way to omit None fields from being returned by api, this 
  will have to be revised for an optimized design

Change-Id: I2b0ef90ea9290dccc181511c63f63cae8c16d2cc
Partial-Bug: #1444758

commit_message:
Use oslo_log instead of openstack.common.log

oslo_log should be used instead of oslo-incubator.
This fixes an error "oslo_config.cfg.DuplicateOptError:
duplicate option: default_log_levels" when os-brick is imported
to projects using oslo_config and oslo_log.

Change-Id: Ic38c548bd39bc8ce68bd70d2b0693f6d0c0c5399
Closes-Bug: #1443681

commit_message:
Merge flavor response schema into one file

After removing v3 schemas, we have only 1 set of schemas for v2 (/v2.1)
APIs but those end up in scattered structure.

Schema files needs to be re arranged into a clean structure. Any
resource schema should be defined in single file for better readability.

This patch merge the flavor response schema into one file.

Partially implements blueprint rearrange-nova-response-schemas

Change-Id: I2f660ce072fe199b4ed4d51ac2267b871d82ef83

commit_message:
Rearrange keypairs response schema into one file

After removing v3 schemas, we have only 1 set of schemas for v2 (/v2.1)
APIs but those end up in scattered structure.

Schema files needs to be re arranged into a clean structure. Any
resource schema should be defined in single file for better readability.

This patch rearrange the keypairs response schema into one file.

Partially implements blueprint rearrange-nova-response-schemas

Change-Id: I76ed40fbe4999c3ee84c4377a6f14fc3a2a11061

commit_message:
fix bug in openstack-network-compute.pp

Limitation 'Nova_config<| |> -> Service['nova-network']' has a sense
only when multi_host == true. Moved this to corresponding branch of
the if $multi_host conditional.

Change-Id: Ie293b06c92e97bd101c616827fee25ff2e795791
Closes-bug: 1444122

commit_message:
Arrange quotas response schema into one file

After removing v3 schemas, we have only 1 set of schemas for v2 (/v2.1)
APIs but those end up in scattered structure.

Schema files needs to be re arranged into a clean structure. Any
resource schema should be defined in single file for better readability.

This patch merge quotas response schema into one file.
Also rename schema names according to their API.

Partially implements blueprint rearrange-nova-response-schemas

Change-Id: I2378e019353f551a3ac49666edd5ecb561b5b6ed

commit_message:
[install-guide] change "API endpoints" to "API endpoint"

An API endpoint on Keystone uses several URLs. We normally (not for
heat) only have one API endpoint for a service in the installation guide.

Change-Id: Idb22a6e0c06382e9e8069eed6e16e69c9c512bb3

There is a race in attach/detach of a volume where the volume status
goes to 'in-use' before the bdm.connection_info data is stored in the
database. Since attach is a cast, the caller can see the volume go to
'in-use' and immediately try to detach the volume and blow up in the
compute manager because bdm.connection_info isn't set stored in the

calling volume_api.attach_volume (which sets the volume status to

commit_message:
Save bdm.connection_info before calling volume_api.attach_volume

There is a race in attach/detach of a volume where the volume status
goes to 'in-use' before the bdm.connection_info data is stored in the
database. Since attach is a cast, the caller can see the volume go to
'in-use' and immediately try to detach the volume and blow up in the
compute manager because bdm.connection_info isn't set stored in the
database.

This fixes the issue by saving the connection_info immediately before
calling volume_api.attach_volume (which sets the volume status to
'in-use').

Closes-Bug: #1327218

Conflicts:
        nova/tests/unit/compute/test_compute.py
        nova/tests/unit/virt/test_block_device.py
        nova/virt/block_device.py

NOTE(mriedem): The block_device conflicts are due to using dot
notation when accessing object fields and in kilo the context is
no longer passed to bdm.save(). The test conflicts are due to moving
the test modules in kilo and passing the context on save().

Change-Id: Ib95c8f7b66aca0c4ac7b92d140cbeb5e85c2717f
(cherry picked from commit 6fb2ef96d6aaf9ca0ad394fd7621ef1e6003f5a1)

commit_message:
libvirt: remove pointless loop after live migration finishes

The libvirt 'migrateToURI' API(s) all block the caller until the
live migration operation has completed. As such, the timer call
used to check if live migration has completed is entirely pointless.
It appears this is code left over from the very first impl of live
migration in Nova, when Nova would simply shell out to the 'virsh'
command instead of using the libvirt APIs. Even back then though
it looks like it was redundant, since the command being spawned
would also block until live migration was finished.

Conflicts:
	nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py

Related-bug: #1414065
Change-Id: Ib3906ef8564a986f7c0e980774e4ed76b3f93a38
(cherry-pick from commit 584a44f0157e84ce0100da6ee4f7b94bbb4088e3)

makes uri unique to avoid duplicated pools

I added an index to the mongodb collection to make uri unique and
avoid the creation of pools with duplicated URIs.

Closes-bug: 1416206

commit_message:
Fix db-sync dependencies

W/o this change, some config changes could
be not synced to db and neutron-server service
start not aligned with db sync process

The solution is to fix the dependencies for
Neutron_config stanzas before db sync exec
and for n-server service - after db sync

Closes-bug: #1384133

Change-Id: I769b6e7ddb567a21a91eeb77375213c131a3d396
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
(cherry picked from commit d7c8d2327a0d46a79ca6519762f088efa8e7373a)

commit_message:
remove stable-compat jobs from libs with stable branches

We don't need to run the backwards-compatibility tests for libraries
that have stable branches, because the master branch of the library will
never be used in the stable branch tests for applications.

Since the job macros are no longer used, remove them, too.

Change-Id: Ie38c5d213279c94a3aae5a69d2c30a3a67f0e391

[{'created': '2015-04-13 04:14:07.000000000', 'message': "Don't provide backends from __all__ in persistence

Token persistence __init__ specified 'backends' in __all__ however this
was never actually imported to be exposed. This could cause issues from
apidoc as there was no code to match the expected symbols.

Removing 'backends' rather than importing it as we shouldn't import code
we don't use.

Change-Id: Ic87371ffb2f65ae8e933f091bb05faaa64a342d2
"}]
commit_message:
Don't provide backends from __all__ in persistence

Token persistence __init__ specified 'backends' in __all__ however this
was never actually imported to be exposed. This could cause issues from
apidoc as there was no code to match the expected symbols.

Removing 'backends' rather than importing it as we shouldn't import code
we don't use.

Change-Id: Ic87371ffb2f65ae8e933f091bb05faaa64a342d2

commit_message:
Refactor sql filter code for clarity

The sql filter code was not clear.

 - The "hint" parameter was passed into functions that don't use it,
   so stop passing this parameter.
 - The parameter docstrings should specify the type normally
 - It should be clear that the cumulative_filter_dict parameter is
   mutated, so don't return it.

Change-Id: I524b03e673b61dbd436abeb9b335c4a62d163771

commit_message:
Make neutron_plugin_ml2 before db-sync

W/o this change some of config changes for
ml2 plugin could be not synced to db.

Solution is to add a notify on db-sync
for all Neutron_plugin_ml2 stanzas

Closes-bug: #1384119

Change-Id: I23f6bca99e1c077804011897814649419da326d4
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
(cherry picked from commit 53688bf2b26682474427f31202756d3217ff20f5)

commit_message:
Implement serverspec elements

serverspec aims to run service validation during TripleO/Puppet
deployment by using step-by-step workflow.

Example: step 1 contains MySQL Galera cluster, so Puppet will take care
of configuration and serverspec will ensure MySQL is actually up and
running, otherwise we consider the stack failed.

This patchs:
* Installs serverspec by using Gem (source).
  For now, there is no package for any distribution, so until we have one,
  let's use source method by running `gem install`, that will take care of
  serverspec and dependencies.
* Installs serverspec-tests from rdo-management.
  For now, serverspec-tests are hosted on github/rdo-management, so
  until we have packaging, we use source install method.

Change-Id: I8efc9a2278e972fe0c61e12823a9250a4a1bc27d

commit_message:
Rebase on pypowervm Enums

Recent pypowervm changes moved pypowervm.tasks.hdisk.LUA_STATUS_* and
LUA_TYPE_* into enums LUAStatus and LUAType and renamed all existing
enumerations.  This change set accomodates those shifts.

Change-Id: I06507d26aba138336d2e8a7480bf03501e773ec7

commit_message:
Deprecate use of cache in list_volumes

The more proactive approach is to invalidate rather than use
cache=False. In all cases, we are about to update, or have just updated,
the item that is in the cache. This will provide more liveness for other
cache users with a shared cache, and will provide less skew between our
own queries to the cache versus reality.

Change-Id: I5a41a3d21fd451f5432daa4e268b57328a9ad90f

When tempest uses identity v3 - either because it's forced by a
test, or because it's configured as default, accounts can still
work with v2 accounts configured in accounts.yaml, under the
assumption that those accounts belong to
CONF.identity.admin_domain_name. The domain name is added on the

commit_message:
FIx Accounts with identity v3 and v2 data in yaml

When tempest uses identity v3 - either because it's forced by a
test, or because it's configured as default, accounts can still
work with v2 accounts configured in accounts.yaml, under the
assumption that those accounts belong to
CONF.identity.admin_domain_name. The domain name is added on the
fly to newly created credentials by cred_provider, however this
is not accounted for in the get_hash function - fixing that.

Change-Id: Id0e72b9a8b85fdc682b9e14c39ecc1d8495ef35c

commit_message:
Catalog: Set correct sort_dir for next/prev page buttons

Before, navigating Next and Previous page used incorrect sort_dir and
incorrect markers because of that. Now marker chosed for next/prev link
is chosen by inspecting current sort_dir.

Change-Id: If181bf6c243878cb798129e69618912eec8c4dcd
Closes-Bug: #1439020

commit_message:
Document Ceilometer Central active-active HA

Since Juno, it is possible to run multiple ceilometer-central
agents, and have them coordinate using workload partitioning.

Change-Id: Id46712c36f9260781bf2abcc03c3fea88cd7ed47
Closes-bug: #1437312

While I agree size should be a config option its value should remain, as it is currently set.  Setting the default to 32K or something other than the ping commands default isn’t what people would expect and could break backwards compatibility.'}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2015-03-06 18:25:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

AFAIK the ping by default does not prohibits smaller fragemtns,
the sender just needs to be able to receive 'fragmentation needed' message and everything should be happy. The fragmentation not needed to be done on the networking device.

The ip packet can be splited to multiple frames, if it does not fits into one.

http://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/generic-routing-encapsulation-gre/25885-pmtud-ipfrag.html

I do not have unusual network connection from my home to google: 

 ping -s 32000 8.8.8.8 
 PING 8.8.8.8 (8.8.8.8) 32000(32028) bytes of data.
 32008 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=52 time=256 ms
 32008 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=2 ttl=52 time=256 ms"}, {'account_id': 12378, 'date': '2015-03-06 20:57:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

My scenario tests use this patch to test many different packet sizes including the example you have given.    Since I have no control over how the different OSs would fragment the 32k I couldn’t guarantee that we wouldn’t hit one of the cases outlined in the MTU advertisement and selection BP where packets get dropped.   

I just don’t think changing the default behavior is a good idea.   If we set the default size to 32k (could go to 65507 on Cirros) and someone has a test that uses this method the number of pkts traversing the vlan in a multi node environment, pinging east/west will increase from 2 pkts to 44 pkts.  If they are checking pkt counts on their network devices as part of the test I would expect their tests to start to fail after this patch went through.'}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2015-03-09 08:23:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

Are you planning to submit those to review ?

IMHO this one of the reason why we create tests to hit those issues.
ping -s 32384; should be able to pass if everything is configured properly, do you agree ?

"If they are checking pkt counts on their network devices as part of the test I would expect their tests to start to fail after this patch went through"

Not really supported operation with tempest. commit_message:
Update linux client to support basic MTU testing

BP MTU selection and adervertisement requires sending pkts of known
sizes to verify MTU.  This patch allows basic MTU testing via the
linux_client

Change-Id: Ia98ad49bad9ebbf783de599689b4684d31fadca6

I misunderstood the purpose of the patch when I first read it. I'm still strongly -1 because the "noop" driver (and the options Christian is configuring here) are all passed through to oslo.messaging. The options read for the "noop" driver and "rabbit" driver are completely disjoint which means there is no *need* to configure this.

rpc_backend has a default value in oslo.messaging (meaning there's no need to specify it here). When noop is chosen as the notification_driver, a Noop Driver is created and used as the driver for the transport object in oslo.messaging. We in glance then pass that to oslo.messaging's Notifier class. I haven't yet had the chance to test this out in devstack or a more realistic installation, but this definitely looks unnecessary.'}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-02-12 20:01:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Sorry all, apparently I'm not being very clear.

If the notification_driver chosen is "noop" there should be absolutely no need to configure anything for rabbit. Christian, if you're seeing issues with this it's either a bug in oslo.messaging or Glance and you should file a bug there.'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-02-13 07:46:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1

Yes I know that it should not be necessary to enable messaging when using the noop messaging driver. But at the moment it is necessary. I checked this on SLES11 SP3 and with noop and unconfigured messaging it is not possible to create new images. I will have a look at Glance and oslo.messaging itself if there is some kind of issue and will update this revie request.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-03-13 06:09:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Any updates, Christian?'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2015-04-16 14:05:36.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

tested with kilo, i cannot reproduce the behavior at the moment'}]

commit_message:
[install-guide] configure messaging for Glance

While using noop as notification_driver it is still necessary to
configure messaging for Glance. Without configuration messaging
it is not possible to create new images.

This is an example output while trying to create a new image
of a Glance API service configured like described in the install
guide at the moment.

Connecting to AMQP server on localhost
AMQP server localhost:5672 closed the connection. Check login
credentials: Socket closed
Delaying reconnect for 1.0 seconds...

Change-Id: Ib387b22794cdf05f55cf4f6206390cc2f98bd6ac

commit_message:
Revised credential database table definition

This patch adds a project column to the credential table. With this new
column, we will be using (user, project) as the primary key for query.
The reason for this is that a trust may be only valid within a specified
project, while a user may be working on a different project for service
requesting.

Change-Id: Ie5f62c1d8225bbfd37fb6fed8baedd52a004e203

commit_message:
API: Proxy neutron configuration to guest instance

Currently the metadata service only contains minimal network
information. Like user_data and vendor_data, we should also provide
network_data. Really we should provide all the information we can
(from neutron) in both config drive and metadata service.

blueprint metadata-service-network-info

Change-Id: I24f86141fecb76e19e019daa537e89ca236c67c8
Previously-approved: Kilo

[{'created': '2015-04-10 22:19:29.000000000', 'message': 'Change location to be a param, not a property

The location property of the glance_image type has nearly identical
functionality as the source param, yet one is a param and one is a
property. It is possible to change either of these for a glance image,
but only if it is as of yet unset, and therefore unsaved. It is not
possible to change the location of a glance image once it has been
saved, nor is it possible to query it afterward. Since having location
be a property when it is usually unsettable and is always unqueryable
does not make much sense, we change it to be a param to be consistent
with the source param.

Change-Id: I686c3fec9bf571d18e282888c626d795c9958a6b
'}]
commit_message:
Change location to be a param, not a property

The location property of the glance_image type has nearly identical
functionality as the source param, yet one is a param and one is a
property. It is possible to change either of these for a glance image,
but only if it is as of yet unset, and therefore unsaved. It is not
possible to change the location of a glance image once it has been
saved, nor is it possible to query it afterward. Since having location
be a property when it is usually unsettable and is always unqueryable
does not make much sense, we change it to be a param to be consistent
with the source param.

Change-Id: I686c3fec9bf571d18e282888c626d795c9958a6b

commit_message:
Wrap ironicclient methods that leak objects

Wrap calls to python-ironicclient methods that leak objects instead
of dictionaries, so dictionaries are only returned moving forward.

Change-Id: I6483ac8c0c316d1a4682e6327d7d5c90498c65f3

commit_message:
init: install openstack-glance on RH platforms

Packaging in RH has some dependencies issues where when installing
openstack-glance-api & openstack-glance-registry won't install openstack-glance.

It breaks some CIs, included TripleO. While some agreement is done in
packaging, we fix it in Puppet.
This patch should be reverted once packaging is finished for Kilo in
RDO.

Closes-bug: #1444974

Change-Id: I33ba58184e15f228958d4d0376d2d2ec52b50b26

commit_message:
generatepot-rst: Fix to work with mawk

Ubuntu uses mawk by default which does not know about the regex feature
"{32}". Use "+" instead for a more portable regex.

Change-Id: I9fd52437eb332dedc9bf977173beda93f984843f

commit_message:
devstack: Start ovn-nbd and ovn-controller

The two OVN daemons now exist, so start them in a devstack
environment.  In passing, have all daemons create a log file and make
sure ovsdb-server has finished starting before interacting with it.

Change-Id: I8c3d2d19262d62e721352dc9cb868b0010fc84cd

commit_message:
IBP Got rid of md for /boot

Centos does use legacy grub, and it is
only able to boot from md with metadata 0.9.
So, we are limited to have not more than 28 disks
on a node because current version of volume
manager assumes /boot is spread over all disks and
0.9 metadata does not support more than 28.
To avoid this limitation we've got rid of using
md for /boot completely.

Change-Id: I08398453625a4e9136d67989c7ebea41cb9cb766
Closes-Bug: #1340414

commit_message:
Remove cloud-init package

Cloud-init package is already present if IBP is used and we do not use it at all.
It just lead that during reboot node is waiting 120 seconds.

DocImpact: Please mention that we remove cloud-init after first reboot
   https://review.openstack.org/#/c/147675/

Change-Id: I1600a3538cf8b758a098e0f770db176539192976
Closes-bug: #1442572

commit_message:
Make neutron_plugin_ml2 before db-sync

W/o this change some of config changes for
ml2 plugin could be not synced to db.

Solution is to add a notify on db-sync
for all Neutron_plugin_ml2 stanzas

Closes-bug: #1384119

Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
(cherry picked from commit 53688bf2b26682474427f31202756d3217ff20f5)

Conflicts:
	manifests/plugins/ml2.pp

Change-Id: I4fde4c26f033571eec9f8bbc09a33eb3addd5a9c

commit_message:
trivial fix to pacemaker provider

without this change REXML make exception with message:
REXML::Element is not a valid input stream.  It must walk  (RuntimeError)
like either a String, an IO, or a Source.

Change-Id: I3d630883293edae10724c8505f899c60ac09a393

The reason is that in V2 tenant-name and tenant-id can be called project-name and project-id so then you need to differentiate them'}, {'account_id': 10608, 'date': '2015-03-31 20:49:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

That's completely incorrect, Fabio. In keystone v2 there was tenant_id/name (not v3). With keystone v3 there is project_id/name (replacing tenant_id/name) PLUS project_domain_id/name (which is necessary because the project_id/name is only unique within a given domain). With keystone v3 you have to specify both the project and the domain of that project."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-31 21:30:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Then it uses either the project id or the tenant id if a project id wasn't supplied:
https://github.com/openstack/python-ceilometerclient/blob/master/ceilometerclient/client.py#L160
and then it passes along to Keystone to find the session:
https://github.com/openstack/python-ceilometerclient/blob/master/ceilometerclient/client.py#L170

commit_message:
ceilometerclient fails with keystone v3 auth

When attempting to use keystone v3 Password authentication,
ceilometerclient is failing to pass the project information to
keystoneclient, which results in an unscoped token that lacks the

commit_message:
Fixes bug with Client function not setting up SSL params

There are instances where some applications (heat, rally) instantiate
ceilometer client using Client function (instead of get_client) which
doesn't use the insecure and verify params properly. This fix will address
that.

Change-Id: I2f6346496e6ee36b5cd97ec6d9a732431532ff96
Closes-Bug: #1428370

commit_message:
Support unicode for alarm

We're using ceilometer.common.utils.print_dict() for displaying alarm,
but assume only contain ascii characters, which will cause UnicodeEncodeError
when alarm's name or description has unicode characters.

The oslo-incubator.cliutils.print_dict() is more friendly to unicode,
but it has no sort option, and has different line wrap strategy. Since
the upstream improvement can be low progress, this patch adds unicode
support based on current code.

Change-Id: Ia58d5813c6f80cb8b44bf7636e1efc0cdd6e6d5b
Closes-Bug: #1412300

commit_message:
Fix vmware attributes for old clusters

Upgraded clusters from 6.0 haven't vmware attributes
so we should exclude it from pre-deployment check

Change-Id: I2b56d645f4626f1a67e7203f917ab2fd4f8b70af
Closes-Bug:#1442499

commit_message:
Enable specified project_id in CLI commands

After we port to oslo-incubator.apiclient, the project_id can no
longer be specified for alarm-{,threhsold,combination}-{create,update}
and sample-create, this is because client.AuthPlugin registers a CLI
argument named --os-project-id which will shadow the project-id
argument.

Since os-project-id is used for Keystone V3 API, we should not
remove it from AuthPlugin, so this patch moves the dest of project_id
to {alarm,sample}_project_id, and adds a decorator to restore shadowed
project_id field when we call v2 client.

Change-Id: I0ce2416dccd61eb50584799e6df0b8c45d44cdda
Closes-Bug: #1393489

commit_message:
Pin puppetlabs-concat to 1.2.1 in fixtures

Puppet Labs is in the process of releasing a 2.0.0 version of
puppetlabs-concat, which will have many breaking changes that affect
many dependent modules. Changes have been merged to master, but not yet
released. While we figure out what changes we need to make in our own
modules and wait for updates in dependent modules, we should just pin
to a stable version.

This module declared concat twice in the fixtures, so we also remove
the second one so that pinning is effective.

Conflicts:
	.fixtures.yml

Change-Id: I53f6bd56099287bfc075bffb24a9ab4be8133cab
(cherry picked from commit 2b3a328ea6776a74e1335c7d800763420b403916)

commit_message:
Pin puppetlabs-concat to 1.2.1 in fixtures

Puppet Labs is in the process of releasing a 2.0.0 version of
puppetlabs-concat, which will have many breaking changes that affect
many dependent modules. Changes have been merged to master, but not yet
released. While we figure out what changes we need to make in our own
modules and wait for updates in dependent modules, we should just pin
to a stable version.

Conflicts:

commit_message:
refactor how provider starts child process

in very rare cases processes created by puppet return
before waiting for the child process to finish. this
leads to the issue when pacemaker provider
starts working with shadow xml copies before they are even created.

this fix refactors how provider starts child process using system function instead of fork&exec pair

testing showed that the issue goes away after this leaving all the other functions untouched

Change-Id: I0c48d974f915e1a3c848beddd9c8421ce00180b6
Closes-bug: #1444915

commit_message:
Pin puppetlabs-concat to 1.2.1 in fixtures

Puppet Labs is in the process of releasing a 2.0.0 version of
puppetlabs-concat, which will have many breaking changes that affect
many dependent modules. Changes have been merged to master, but not yet
released. While we figure out what changes we need to make in our own
modules and wait for updates in dependent modules, we should just pin
to a stable version.

Conflicts:
	.fixtures.yml

Change-Id: I0f9a65452c71f0d1392dad4e13418065e911a01b
(cherry picked from commit f083cb4f34dd35fb81d0495a8f56e783863664b4)

commit_message:
alarm: Use new gnocchi aggregation API

Since https://review.openstack.org/#/c/163462/ and
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/162649/4 in gnocchi, all kind of aggregations
have been moved in the same URI namespace (/v1/aggregation/...)
and we can use complex query to make aggregation across multiples metrics.

This change sync the ceilometerclient alarm shell to match these
changes.

Change-Id: I5717a4604af5505dfb8c56463e2bdb86c59e41ce
(cherry picked from commit db48aa28b169fa8df01020d54a20e644c9a0b7df)

commit_message:
Pin puppetlabs-concat to 1.2.1 in fixtures

Puppet Labs is in the process of releasing a 2.0.0 version of
puppetlabs-concat, which will have many breaking changes that affect
many dependent modules. Changes have been merged to master, but not yet
released. While we figure out what changes we need to make in our own
modules and wait for updates in dependent modules, we should just pin
to a stable version.

Change-Id: I446db00bdf456ac475cb940f00db5b3a108ab203
(cherry picked from commit feacfd425186acf86237306c99d4c5a7cdbc2867)

commit_message:
Forbid booting of QCOW2 images with virtual_size > root_gb

Currently, it's possible to boot an instance from a QCOW2 image,
which has virtual_size bigger than one allowed by the given flavor
(root_gb).

The issue is caused by two different problems in the code:

1) typo in get_disk_size() has made it always return None and
   effectively disabled verify_base_size() checks

2) Rbd image backend skips the verify_base_size() step for
   'cached' images (the one with base files), so it is possible to
   boot an instance using a larger flavor once and then use smaller
   flavors to boot the same image, even if allowed root_gb size is
   smaller than the image virtual size

Closes-Bug: #1429093

Change-Id: I383130e5f8cc288f4b428ed43fe4d3aba7169473

commit_message:
Never show Deployment Mode step in the wizard

The step should be kept in the config because:
- we still need to support it for older releases
- we still need to send 'mode' property when creating a cluster

Change-Id: I39b76deb5a16a2b6cb24cd1bb751267c99531d19
Related-Bug: #1428054

commit_message:
Return detailed metric info on create

When a POST is made on /v1/metric return the full
metric object info instead of just id and archive
policy name like we do now. The is so the metric
api is consistant with the rest and the behavior
is now different as in we allow an optional name
so more info returned would be helpful.

Change-Id: I66681550b0534e6dfcd7fecee80ba01bf6cc73da

commit_message:
Pass correct context to get_by_compute_node()

A recent change to the PciDevTracker class allowed for the passing of
the compute node ID to the __init__() method, where
PciDevsList.get_by_compute_node() was called with a 'context' parameter,
which wasn't defined, resulting in the imported context module being
passed instead.

This change requires that the context be passed in to the __init__() for
the PciDevTracker class, and that that be used to create the
PciDevsList. The existing import of the context module is no longer
needed in the pci/manager.py file, so the conflict is no longer a
problem. The only place in the code that currently instantiates a
PciDevTracker object is in the ResourceTracker, so that has been updated
to pass in the context. A unit test to check for context has also been
added.

(cherry picked from commit 50ee9dd76e8955dd57e5a7318be023c76c462f67)

Conflicts:
	nova/compute/resource_tracker.py
	nova/tests/pci/test_pci_manager.py

Closes-Bug: #1408480
Change-Id: Id136eabacb00e4381c03f12d8484fc90a5eb48b1

commit_message:
Don't apply the wrong Etag validation to rebuilt fragments

Because of the object-server's interaction with ssync sender's
X-Backend-Replication-Headers when a object (or fragment archive) is
pushed unmodified to another node it's ETag value is duped into the
recieving ends metadata as Etag.  This interacts poorly with the
reconstructor's RebuildingECDiskFileStream which can not know ahead of
time the ETag of the fragment archive being rebuilt.

Don't send the Etag from the local source fragment archive being used as
the basis for the rebuilt fragent archive's metadata along to ssync.

Change-Id: Ie59ad93a67a7f439c9a84cd9cff31540f97f334a

[{'created': '2015-04-15 13:21:03.000000000', 'message': "Push OpenStack libraries stable caps

Cap all OpenStack libraries to current version <X.Y+1.0 so that
we keep X.Y.* for potential stable updates.

We don't need to sdo that for Oslo libraries since they were
capped when their stable branches were cut earlier in the cycle.

commit_message:
Push OpenStack libraries stable caps

Cap all OpenStack libraries to current version <X.Y+1.0 so that
we keep X.Y.* for potential stable updates.

We don't need to sdo that for Oslo libraries since they were
capped when their stable branches were cut earlier in the cycle.

Change-Id: Id4c2037f54a8cea7a7410ea443cd7c8ec74c65ba

commit_message:
Put in Sahara repo actual scenario files

Now scenario files placed in Sahara repo aren't equal to scenario files
which actually is using in Sahara CI.

Also we want to use scenario files from Sahara repo, instead
Sahara CI repo, so we need to update this files.

Change-Id: Id6adb8f89934ffe4ceb85cf7c12359dca8eff09e

instead of new one.

Here's the steps when issue occurs:

* One container isn't running due to some reason (for instance, it
  failed). The supervisor scheduled to start it again soon.
* The fuel_upgrade script stops supervisor's processes. They will be
  stopped and won't be started again by supervisor (even if they have

* Point supervisor to new config folder (which is empty by now).
* Restart supervisor, so it forget old configs and will use no of them.
* Upload images and create new containers.
* Generate new supervisor configs and restart supervisor in order to
  apply them (supervisor's processes will be attached automatically
  to running docker containers).

commit_message:
Change docker upgrade steps

We used to have an 'error-prone' approach of making Docker upgrades,
and in really rare cases we had an old container in 'running' state
instead of new one.

Here's the steps when issue occurs:

* One container isn't running due to some reason (for instance, it
  failed). The supervisor scheduled to start it again soon.
* The fuel_upgrade script stops supervisor's processes. They will be
  stopped and won't be started again by supervisor (even if they have
  autostart=true setting).
* The container, which wasn't run by the time we was stopping them,
  is untouched. It's still scheduled to be running soon.
* The fuel_upgrade script stops Docker containers, but one of them
  will be starting again and again because of that working supervisor
  process.

In order to avoid this situation, we have to do the following things:

* Point supervisor to new config folder (which is empty by now).
* Restart supervisor, so it forget old configs and will use no of them.
* Upload images and create new containers.
* Generate new supervisor configs and restart supervisor in order to
  apply them (supervisor's processes will be attached automatically
  to running docker containers).

Signed-off-by: Igor Kalnitsky <igor@kalnitsky.org>

Change-Id: Ibc133b4471878efeffeb232192b4540d26401fae
Closes-Bug: #1441693

To monitor the number of open connections a new monitoring playbook has
been added called network.yml. This playbook will need to be run as
part of the deployment when the other monitoring playbooks are used.

This playbook will create a new alarm that will alert when > 90% of
nf_conntrack_max is reached by nf_conntrack_count. The data is
collected using the conntrack_count.py plugin in the rcbops-maas repo.

Closes-Bug: #1439604
Change-Id: I8aed6df1157f5337b531ba24ec566200b6e67af3
(cherry picked from commit e7158df9588aa990b7a239f84b5591ed43b84e8f)

commit_message:
Add network.yml monitoring playbook

To monitor the number of open connections a new monitoring playbook has
been added called network.yml. This playbook will need to be run as
part of the deployment when the other monitoring playbooks are used.

This playbook will create a new alarm that will alert when > 90% of
nf_conntrack_max is reached by nf_conntrack_count. The data is
collected using the conntrack_count.py plugin in the rcbops-maas repo.

Closes-Bug: #1439604
Change-Id: I8aed6df1157f5337b531ba24ec566200b6e67af3
(cherry picked from commit e7158df9588aa990b7a239f84b5591ed43b84e8f)

commit_message:
[install-guide] [yum] install Memcached in "Add the Identity service"

In step 2c in "To install and configure the Identity service components"
we configure the usage of memcache. Memcached is not
installed/enabled/started by default on CentOS/RHEL/Fedora and has to be
installed/enabled/started first.

Partially implements bp installguide-kilo.

Change-Id: If6070fb5c24c0681634ac003d68e3cdeb8222f5a

commit_message:
Adds rsyslog-client tag to install plays

In order to ease the addition of external log receivers this adds an
rsyslog-client tag to the installation plays.  This allows us to run
openstack-ansible setup-everything.yml --tags rsyslog-client to add
additional logging configuration.

Change-Id: If002f67a626ff5fe3dc06d77c9295ede9369b3dc
Partially-Implements: blueprint master-kilofication

commit_message:
The erlang cookie management for Rabbit OCF

This is a partial backport of the erlang cookie
management for the RabbitMQ OCF. It is disabled
by default as it requires the manual configuration
of the corresponding pacemaker resource and
cannot be done at deployment stage (there is
no synced puppet-rabbitmq module in the 5.1)

Closes-bug: #1440017

Change-Id: I9a3a09e22297697a47dd24651c5bc2c1ad5ba416
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-14 08:20:31.000000000', 'message': 'Auto-removing empty bridges causes race condition

Prerequisite: only one instance is running on the hypervisor
that belongs to the given network

Reproduction:
1. Hard reboot this instance causes the tap device is detached.
2. Linuxbridge-agent remove the bridge because it is empty.
3. The tap device of the instance is re-attached.
4. Cannot find the right bridge because it has been removed.

Solution:
1. Add an option to enable/disable this feature on the agent side.
2. Add a script to manually clean up those empty bridges.

Change-Id: I65f9af097e5e02130499441589b79a574a79a882
Closes-Bug: #1328546
'}]
commit_message:
Auto-removing empty bridges causes race condition

Prerequisite: only one instance is running on the hypervisor
that belongs to the given network

Reproduction:
1. Hard reboot this instance causes the tap device is detached.
2. Linuxbridge-agent remove the bridge because it is empty.
3. The tap device of the instance is re-attached.
4. Cannot find the right bridge because it has been removed.

Solution:
1. Add an option to enable/disable this feature on the agent side.
2. Add a script to manually clean up those empty bridges.

Change-Id: I65f9af097e5e02130499441589b79a574a79a882
Closes-Bug: #1328546

Initial version of a keystone driver

This is an indirection layer for interacting with Keystone service via
OpenStackSDK. The driver hides the details of this interaction through
OpenStackSDK.

errors_out_migration decorator is used in ComputeManager for
finish_resize and resize_instance methods, this decorator
expects to find a kwargs with 'migration' as the key. So
we should fix the calls in _ComputeV4Proxy to send the
migration parameter in kwargs.

Closes-Bug: #1444300
Change-Id: Ie2d7d6e7fd51976a39246ab4c87488065716d767
"}]
commit_message:
Fix proxying finish_resize and resize_instance in _ComputeV4Proxy

errors_out_migration decorator is used in ComputeManager for
finish_resize and resize_instance methods, this decorator
expects to find a kwargs with 'migration' as the key. So
we should fix the calls in _ComputeV4Proxy to send the
migration parameter in kwargs.

Closes-Bug: #1444300
Change-Id: Ie2d7d6e7fd51976a39246ab4c87488065716d767

commit_message:
Fix heartbeat when clean step in progress

The agent returns command_result of None when a command is in progress.
The code assumed it would return an empty dict. Fix the access of
command_result to never return None, and fix the tests to reflect
reality.

Closes-Bug: #1444715
Change-Id: Iae6cd90517cb7b268ce2c089c92f64b09a606a42

commit_message:
Start use error_exit function in AWS LB

Function error_exit is not used in userdata. This patch add check for
running cfn-init, which uses error_exit function.

Change-Id: Ic72862e71024fcb257708b6310f26c9a764088dc
Closes-Bug: #1443829

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-09 22:55:13.000000000', 'message': 'Add YAQL parsing to DSL validation

For DSL specs that support YAQL, add YAQL parsing to the DSL validation.
Currently, YAQL syntax errors are not known until runtime when the YAQL
is parsed and evaluated. This will catch syntax errors in the YAQL string
before the workflow is executed. There are still cases which are not
covered in this patch where YAQL can parse but evaluate fails (i.e.
unrecognized function).

Change-Id: I30ea5c60f26d7c238eb3ecbd4999f03fae3151ce
Implements: blueprint api-validate-dsl

commit_message:
Add YAQL parsing to DSL validation

For DSL specs that support YAQL, add YAQL parsing to the DSL validation.
Currently, YAQL syntax errors are not known until runtime when the YAQL
is parsed and evaluated. This will catch syntax errors in the YAQL string
before the workflow is executed. There are still cases which are not
covered in this patch where YAQL can parse but evaluate fails (i.e.
unrecognized function).

Change-Id: I30ea5c60f26d7c238eb3ecbd4999f03fae3151ce
Implements: blueprint api-validate-dsl

commit_message:
Clarify `attributes` support status for AutoScalingGroup

Clarify that latest HOT is required for path based get_attr
calls using 'outputs' and 'outputs_list'.

Change-Id: I44de426a61726d27616f6dd8a38e676fb2a6fbcc
Closes-Bug: #1444286

> So the downside to this is that it freezes us at the oldest version of mock in use on any of our supported Python's.

Well, my (latest) change delegates the choice of the mock module to oslotest.

oslotest is problably a better place to choose between mock and unittest.mock, since oslotest uses advanced test functions.

In practice, I'm not aware of new shiny feature of mock or unittest.mock, I'm only aware of bugs with Python 3.4 :-)

In unittest.mock doc, I found this "versionchanged":
https://docs.python.org/dev/library/unittest.mock.html#unittest.mock.NonCallableMock

commit_message:
Use unittest.mock on Python 3

The mock module has been added to Python 3.3 as unittest.mock.

The third party mock module doesn't seem to be maintained anymore: the
last commit was in April 2013.

unittest.mock is more recent, has less bugs and is compatible with
Python 3.4. There are bugs on Python 3 in the third party mock module,
examples:

* https://code.google.com/p/mock/issues/detail?id=225
* https://code.google.com/p/mock/issues/detail?id=234

Oslo Messaging hits these issues when running tests on Python 3.4.

Import oslotest to setup six.moves for mock.

Change-Id: Ic160101695cea67eb9bbbfcaddb8d3dac64e6804

commit_message:
Switch default COMPUTESCALE setting down to 1 from 2

By decreasing the number of compute nodes deployed by default
via devtest, we lower the minumum requirements and make
deployment marginally faster; the devtest script aims at
setting up a tripleo development environment so having multiple
computes only seems to make sense in special circumstances.

Change-Id: I2aa9f205246ed1a37371bee2d1cb113193462bc5

commit_message:
Add method in Agent class to allow message handling extensions

A new method is added to handle message creation separately from
the send logic. This will allow to extend Agent code by using inheritance
so that there is no need to rewrite send method in order to change
message content.

Closes-Bug: #1444547
Change-Id: I95e35974f7df017383df206293e8a7c93af04489

commit_message:
Install 'yum-plugin-priorities' on all slaves

Since Fuel 6.1 we are able to work with custom set of repos with custom
priorities. By default, yum is unable to work with them, but it could be
fixed by installing 'yum-plugin-priorities'.

Change-Id: I6b36c79caf0d853c8979f87b8526c71699a75fe4
Related-Bug: #1440074

commit_message:
Fixes port acquiring logic in DockerStandaloneHost

Previous code used integer keys in port map. But because
JSON doesn't support integer keys they were converted
to corresponding string representations and were not
found on subsequent deployments

Change-Id: I0477a043854a5ed78545d3b944397cdbf2352bd8
Closes-Bug: #1444681

commit_message:
Disable resources cleanup for DHCP agent by default

Now all resources created by DHCP agent (namespaces, processes) are removed by
Pacemaker on agent start and stop. This operation can be rather slow when many
networks exist in a cloud, and timeout will turn the resource to unmanaged
state. To avoid such cases resources are kept by default.
It also helps to avoid service interruption because all resource have to be
re-created by the agent in case of restart.

Change-Id: Ia6cdc3b86b162f4614a8ed93838d3e09d9126ffc
Closes-bug: #1436414
(cherry picked from commit d6cff81273fe05e59ac0b0a4c7f94cb56d648f86)

commit_message:
Trust fetch and creation logic

This patch adds trust check and creation logic in middleware. The
middleware will first check if there is a trust between the service
requestor and the 'senlin' user in the current project. If not trust is
found, a new trust will be created and used later.

Change-Id: I8bfb4a84055cc8c80e491cddc8db2a17011985bf

[{'created': '2015-04-08 14:29:38.000000000', 'message': 'Reduce DB calls when getting an image

Right now if you want to get a single image, two queries need to be
executed:
- Get image + associated locations and properties
- Get associated tags for image

Proposed solution combines these two queries into single one which gets
image and all related data - locations, properties and tags. Similar
pattern has been already implemented when querying for list of images.

Change-Id: Ic4424bb1eb1769d8f621ebe111d95961ecf08479
Closes-Bug: 1434578
'}]
commit_message:
Reduce DB calls when getting an image

Right now if you want to get a single image, two queries need to be
executed:
- Get image + associated locations and properties
- Get associated tags for image

Proposed solution combines these two queries into single one which gets
image and all related data - locations, properties and tags. Similar
pattern has been already implemented when querying for list of images.

Change-Id: Ic4424bb1eb1769d8f621ebe111d95961ecf08479
Closes-Bug: 1434578

commit_message:
broadcast data to relevant queues only

system resources are required to broadcast messages to queues. currently,
when requeuing data for pipeline coordination, we broadcast to all
queues. this patch adds a check to broadcast only to relevant
pipelines.

Change-Id: If4cee643537fe136fdcf66acc35e2671dbd2ac74
Closes-Bug: #1436489

commit_message:
Pin puppetlabs-concat to 1.2.1 in fixtures

Puppet Labs is in the process of releasing a 2.0.0 version of
puppetlabs-concat, which will have many breaking changes that affect
many dependent modules. Changes have been merged to master, but not yet
released. While we figure out what changes we need to make in our own
modules and wait for updates in dependent modules, we should just pin
to a stable version.

This module declared concat twice in the fixtures, so we also remove
the second one so that pinning is effective.

Change-Id: I53f6bd56099287bfc075bffb24a9ab4be8133cab

commit_message:
Pin puppetlabs-concat to 1.2.1 in fixtures

Puppet Labs is in the process of releasing a 2.0.0 version of
puppetlabs-concat, which will have many breaking changes that affect
many dependent modules. Changes have been merged to master, but not yet
released. While we figure out what changes we need to make in our own
modules and wait for updates in dependent modules, we should just pin
to a stable version.

Change-Id: I555f9164f1d4acde9e3ffe7a4d1c7966e2bc04bf

commit_message:
Unpin rabbitmq module

The ref 'origin/4.x' does not exist, so the spec_prep rake task does
not use that ref and instead just pulls down master. The rabbitmq
resources in the openstacklib module work with the latest version of
puppetlabs-rabbitmq, so this hasn't caused a problem, just a strange
message during testing. This change unpins it because it isn't
necessary and the pin doesn't work.

Change-Id: I4057cf1083ee3959ae963fcba795505cba4f1a82

puppetlabs-concat, which will have many breaking changes that affect
many dependent modules. Changes have been merged to master, but not yet
released. While we figure out what changes we need to make in our own
modules and wait for updates in dependent modules, we should just pin
to a stable version.

commit_message:
Add requirements to docker host and k8s cluster

Since now, all flavors that have less than 10 GB disk will
not be added to the possible selection.

Also, unnecessary backslashes were removed.

Change-Id: I0839a4252957acd2be9dddbd335674c22c3d57a5

commit_message:
Pin puppetlabs-concat to 1.2.1 in fixtures

Puppet Labs is in the process of releasing a 2.0.0 version of
puppetlabs-concat, which will have many breaking changes that affect
many dependent modules. Changes have been merged to master, but not yet
released. While we figure out what changes we need to make in our own
modules and wait for updates in dependent modules, we should just pin
to a stable version.

Change-Id: I6253077853e800d081b9ec88f26c56d58a23108d

commit_message:
Silence logs + errors when stopping and group membership lost

It is not useful to log a warning with exception backtrace on
stop when we have lost our group membership since at this point
we are leaving the group anyway (and if we already left/do not
exist then this is a tolerable/acceptable failure).

Change-Id: I116642c164bfe63680c10b0a7734bd06176b4b8d

commit_message:
Allow the acquired file to be closed manually

Instead of requiring library users to wait for a GC
pass to close the file descriptor, make it possible
for a explicit close() call to do the same.

This makes it possible for users of these locks to
avoid running out of file descriptors that they are
unable to close.

Change-Id: I3fabc57b2f0f6b1cef45553cac7e04732a9c2489
